d - for 74 \u00e5r siden: Forbudt at se fodbold fra museumsbakken |publisher=Skive Folkeblad |date=3 August 2018 |page=28, Sektion 1, Bagsiden |language=da}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"skiveam-his\">{{cite web |title=Skive Atletik- og Motionsklubs historie - perioden 1901 - 1949 |url=http://skiveam.dk/klubben/om-skive-am/historien/ |website=www.skiveam.dk |publisher=Skive AM |accessdate=21 December 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191221141532/http://skiveam.dk/klubben/om-skive-am/historien/ |archivedate=21 December 2019 |language=da}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"sik-nyh\">{{cite web |title=Nyheder: 11.05-2003 (2. Div.) 23. runde; 06.05-2003 Skive Stadion indvies s\u00f8ndag med lokalopg\u00f8r |url=http://www.skive-ik.dk:80/nyheder.html |website=www.skive-ik.dk |publisher=Skive IK |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030628150945/http://www.skive-ik.dk:80/nyheder.html |archivedate=28 June 2003 |language=da}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"sf-12.05.2002\">{{cite news |title=Skive Stadion t\u00e6t p\u00e5 nyt spadestik |publisher=Skive Folkeblad |date=15 May 2002 |location=Skive |language=da |quote=For to \u00e5r siden brugte Skive Kommune ti millioner kroner til at g\u00f8re idr\u00e6ts-faciliteterne i stand. Stadion fik blandt andet en hel ny l\u00f8bebane af international klasse.}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"sf-14.11.2009\">{{cite news |last1=Kristensen |first1=Jens |title=Skive AM's formand om kommunalreformen: Favorisering af \u00e9n klub gjort tydeligere |publisher=Skive Folkeblad |location=Skive |page=11, Sektion 1 |language=da |date=14 November 2009}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"sf-28.11.2018\">{{cite news |last1=Kristensen |first1=Jens |title=Skive IK Elite: Stadionleje bliver i ro efter investering p\u00e5 2,6 millioner kroner |publisher=Skive Folkeblad |date=28 November 2018 |page=7, Sektion 1 |language=da}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"sf-26.07.2018\">{{cite news |last1=Laursen |first1=Brian |title=Skive Stadion nyder godt af geografisk placering: Nu l\u00f8ber der lidt mindre vand i \u00e5en |publisher=Skive Folkeblad |date=26 July 2018 |page=14, Sektion 1 |language=da}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"drkis\">{{cite book |last1=Mortensen |first1=Niels |title=OMB Skive Bogen version 14 |date=2009 |chapter=Det r\u00f8de klubhus i Skive |publisher=www.detr\u00f8deklubhus.dk |location=Skive |pages=82\u201391 |url=https://www.xn--detrdeklubhus-enb.dk/uf/80000_89999/85246/d7f1dea24327a71527af341894034fff.pdf |accessdate=22 December 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191222031116/https://www.xn--detrdeklubhus-enb.dk/uf/80000_89999/85246/d7f1dea24327a71527af341894034fff.pdf |archivedate=22 December 2019 |language=da}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"sf-09.09.2009\">{{cite news |last1=Kristensen |first1=Jens |title=Skive IK Elite A/S kan snart s\u00e6lge stadion-navn |publisher=Skive Folkeblad |date=9 September 2009 |location=Skive |page=5, Sektion 1 |language=da}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"pol-07.11.2002\">{{cite news |last1=Wilkens |first1=Kristine |title=Fra marken til parken: Lav sol over udstoppede skibonitter |publisher=[[Politiken]] |date=7 November 2002 |page=10, Sektion 2 (Kultur) |language=da}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"sf-28.06.2002\">{{cite news |title=Kaj Ove Madsen bygger stadion f\u00e6rdig |publisher=Skive Folkeblad |date=28 June 2002 |language=da}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"djfh-m\u00e5\">{{cite book |editor1-last=Larsen |editor1-first=Mads D. |editor2-last=Kristensen |editor2-first=Lykke M\u00f8ller |title=De jyske fodboldklubbers historie - Milep\u00e6le, bedrifter og profiler. Om udviklingen i jysk fodbold fortalt med klubbernes egne ord |date=2006 |publisher=[[DBU Jutland|Jydsk Boldspil-Union]] |pages=174\u2013177 |edition=1. udgave, 2. Bind, M til \u00c5 |language=da |chapter=Skive IK}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.skive-ik.dk/fan/stadion Subsection on the official website of Skive IK] {{in lang|da}}\n\n{{Danish 1st Division stadiumlist}}\n\n{{Coord|56|34|5.3|N|9|2|15.8|E|type:landmark_region:DK_scale:2000|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Football venues in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Skive Municipality]]\n[[Category:Skive IK]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Danish association football stadium}}\n{{Infobox stadium\n| name                = Skive Stadion<br />Hancock Arena\n| nickname            = \n| logo_image          = Skive Stadion 20120409.jpg\n| logo_caption        = {{nowrap|View of the stadium during a match in April 2012}}\n| image               =  \n| caption             = \n| fullname            = Skive Stadium\n| former_names        = Skive Stadion (1944-''present'')<br />Sparbank Arena (2010\u20132012)<br />Spar Nord Arena (2012\u20132018)<br />SIK Arena (2018)<br />{{nowrap|Hancock Arena (2018\u2013''present'')}}\n| location            = Engvej 19<br />7800 [[Skive, Denmark|Skive]]\n| coordinates         = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LON|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} -->\n| broke_ground        = May 1941<ref name=\"sik100\"/>\n| built               = 1941\u20131944<ref name=\"sik100\"/>\n| opened              = {{Start date and years ago|df=yes|1944|6|5}}<ref name=\"sik100\"/>\n| renovated           = 1998\u20131999<ref name=\"sik100\"/><ref name=\"sik-nyh\" />, 2002\u20132003<ref name=\"sik-nyh\" />, 2009<ref name=\"skiveam-stadion\" /> and 2010<ref name=\"skiveam-stadion\" />\n| expanded            = 1965\u20131966<ref name=\"djfh-m\u00e5\" />\n| closed              = \n| demolished          = \n| owner               = [[Skive Municipality]]<ref name=\"tvmv-varme\" />\n| operator            = \n| surface             = [[Poaceae#Sports turf|Natural grass]]\n| scoreboard          = \n| cost                = [[Danish krone|DKK]] 130,000 <small>(1944)</small><ref name=\"sik100\"/><br />DKK 10 million <small>(1998\u20131999)</small><ref name=\"sf-12.05.2002\" /><br />DKK 2.6 million <small>(2017)</small><ref name=\"sf-28.11.2018\" />\n| architect           = \n| project_manager     = \n| structural engineer = \n| services engineer   = \n| general_contractor  = \n| main_contractors    = Kaj Ove Madsen A/S <small>(2002-2003)</small><ref name=\"sf-28.06.2002\" />\n| capacity            = 10,000 (523 seatings)<ref name=\"skiveik-stadion\" />\n| suites              = \n| record_attendance   = 10,000 ([[Skive IK]] vs [[Viborg FF]], 19 May 1955)<ref name=\"skiveik-stadion\" /><ref name=\"sik100\" />\n| dimensions          = {{convert|105|x|68|m|yd|1}}<ref name=\"skiveik-stadion\" />\n| acreage             = \n| volume              = \n| tenants             = [[Skive IK]] (1944\u20131997; 2003\u2013''present'')<br />Skive AM (1977\u2013''present'')<br />Arbejdernes IF (1944\u20131946)\n| embedded            =\n| website             = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n\n'''Skive Stadium''' ([[Danish language|Danish]]: '''Skive Stadion''') is an [[Athletics (sport)|athletics]]- and [[association football]] [[stadium]] located in [[Skive, Denmark]], owned and operated by [[Skive Municipality]].<ref name=\"tvmv-varme\" /> It is currently used mostly for [[association football]] matches and is the home stadium of [[Skive IK|Skive Idr\u00e6tsklub]] (association football) and Skive Atletik- og Motionsklub ([[Sport of athletics|athletics]]). The stadium is part of a sport center, which since 2007 has also consisted of a multi-purpose hall named Spar Nord Arena, while the stadium itself includes [[International Association of Athletics Federations|IAAF]] certified athletics and sports facilities such as six round lanes, eight straight lanes, starting blocks, electronic timing, two tracks for the [[long jump]] and [[triple jump]], [[pole vault]] and three throw cages surrounding an association football field.<ref name=\"skiveam-stadion\" /> The ground has a lighting installation with a light intensity of 500 [[lux]] and have been approved for televised [[Danish 1st Division]] matches by the [[Danish Football Association|Danish FA]].<ref name=\"skiveik-stadion\" /> Apart from hosting matches for the [[Danish 1st Division|second highest football league]], the stadium have also staged two men's youth [[Exhibition game|friendlies]] and two [[2016 UEFA Women's Under-19 Championship qualification|European women's youth qualification games]], one for the [[Denmark national football team|Danish national youth team]].<ref name=\"ldb-skive\" /> It has been known as '''Hancock Arena''' for [[Sponsor (commercial)|sponsorship]] reasons since July 2018 and have previously been referred to as '''Sparbank Arena''' (2010\u20132012), '''Spar Nord Arena''' (2012\u20132018) and '''SIK Arena''' (2018).\n\n== History ==\nThe construction of the [[List of football stadiums in Denmark|stadium]] at Engvej broke ground in May 1941, with the last details coming into place in the spring of 1943, and the new stadium was finished in 1944 at a total cost of DKK 130,000.<ref name=\"sik100\" /> As part of the agreement between [[Skive IK]] and [[Skive Municipality]], a new club house was built at the ground at a cost of DKK 12,000 and the club officially moved to Engvej in the spring of 1944.<ref name=\"sik100\" /> The stadium, with a total area of 9.5 [[barrel of land|barrels of land]] located at the [[meadow]] referred as ''Rosens Eng'' next to Karup River, consisted of an exhibition field with athletics courses, two training fields and four tennis courts.<ref name=\"sik100\" /> In the years leading up to the construction of the stadium, the meadow had already been filled up by the municipality as relief work for the unemployed.<ref name=\"drkis\" /> The inauguration of the stadium at Engvej took place on 5 June 1944 ([[Constitution Day (Denmark)|Constitution Day]]) with a programme consisting of a large athletics event with participation of many of the country's strongest athletes and an [[association football]] match in front of nearly 4,000 [[Audience|spectators]].<ref name=\"sik100\" /><ref name=\"skiveam-his\" /> Skive IK, participating in the 1943\u201344 JBU's Mesterskabsr\u00e6kke, lost their association football match against the best placed [[Jutland]]ish league team in the [[1943\u201344 Danish War Tournament|1943\u201344 season]], [[Aarhus Gymnastikforening|Aarhus GF]].<ref name=\"sik100\" /> Arbejdernes Idr\u00e6tsforening (AIF), which was the competing sports team in the city, had their own inauguration of the stadium on 18 June 1944 with music, singing and association football, and their first team in the JBU's Mellemr\u00e6kke played an exhibition match against the local rivals [[Holstebro Boldklub|Holstebro BK]] from the JBU's Mesterskabsr\u00e6kke.<ref name=\"sik100\" />\n\nThe City Council of [[Skive, Denmark|Skive]] made a unanimous decision on 12 June 1944 to prohibit the presence of non-paying [[audience|spectators]] at the north lying [[hill]]side, with the residence of the Skive Museum, during association football matches.<ref name=\"skifol-forbudt\" /> Proposed by the then Street and Road Committee, the ban was meant to discourage potential ''free riders'' from viewing the matches from outside that stadium's gates, which could cost revenue for Skive IK and Skive Municipality.<ref name=\"skifol-forbudt\" /> However, the local [[police]] have never enforced the ban nor spend resources on it, which have not had any significant impact.<ref name=\"skifol-forbudt\" /> In the spring of 1945, the [[Denmark in World War II|German occupying forces]] seizes the stadium facilities and on 8 May 1945 a large parade was held by the [[Danish resistance movement]].<ref name=\"skiveam-his\" /><ref name=\"drkis\" /> Although the construction of a covered spectator stand had to be abandoned due to the stringent rationing of building material during [[World War II]], it was finally built starting from the summer of 1965 to spring 1966 using voluntary labor and with partial financial support from Skive Municipality for the [[building material]]s, and was attached to Skive IK's new club member's house next to the football field \u2014 the house was inaugurated on 28 March 1966.<ref name=\"sik100\" /><ref name=\"drkis\" /><ref name=\"djfh-m\u00e5\" />\n\nThe stadium holds 10,000 people of which 523 are seated at the covered grandstand in the south west side.<ref name=\"skiveik-stadion\" /> The stadium's record attendance was recorded on 19 May 1955 ([[Feast of the Ascension|Ascension Day]]), when sold-out stadium crowd of nearly 10,000 spectators watched the last decisive league match in the [[1954\u201355 Jutland Series]] between the two highest placed teams in the northern division, Skive IK and local rivals [[Viborg FF]], competing for the division title and hence a spot in the [[Jutland Series|1954\u201355 Jutland Championship]] Final and qualification for the [[1954\u201355 Kvalifikationsturneringen]] (popularly known as the ''Danish 4th Division'').<ref name=\"skiveik-stadion\" /><ref name=\"sik100\" /> The [[Danish football league system|level 4]] league match, that Viborg FF won 3\u20132 in windy rain, is reportedly the largest match attendance to a lower ranking Danish league game, outside of the top three divisional structure.<ref name=\"sik100\" /><ref name=\"tipsbladet-skiveik\" />\n\nLarge [[renovation]]s and expansions to the stadium began in 1998. At that point, club members referred to the 55 years old ground as the most outdated [[Danish football league system|division]] stadium in Denmark.<ref name=\"sik100\" /> As a consequence of the first phase, that involved the [[running track]]s for the [[athlete]]s having synthetic coating installed by 1999 and hence upgrading them to [[International Association of Athletics Federations|international standards]], Skive IK was forced to relocate their [[Professionalism in association football|professional association football]] home matches to Egeris Idr\u00e6tsanl\u00e6g (more specifically ''Bane 1'') in the south part of the city \u2014 the team played a last game at the stadium, before the renovations commenced, against [[Skovshoved IF]] in the fall of 1997 as part of their [[1997\u201398 Danish 2nd Division]] campaign.<ref name=\"sik-nyh\" /><ref name=\"skiveam-stadion\" /><ref name=\"sik100\" /><ref name=\"sf-12.05.2002\" /> The club's professional senior team played at their temporary ground until the reconstruction was completed in 2003, while Skive AM was the only club to use the stadium facilities after the completion of phase one.<ref name=\"sik-nyh\" /><ref name=\"pol-07.11.2002\" /> After a 5.5 year displacement period, Skive IK inaugurated the renovated stadium on 11 May 2003 with a derby against [[Holstebro Boldklub|Holstebro BK]] in front of 1,720 spectators as part of a larger celebration program that included [[Public speaking|speeches]], [[cycling]] and athletics competitions.<ref name=\"sik-nyh\" /> The first phase had cost Skive Municipality DKK 10 million, which delayed the second phase of the project due to lack of funds.<ref name=\"sf-12.05.2002\" /> The task of completing phase two was handed to a local Skive contractor, Kaj Ove Madsen A/S.<ref name=\"sf-28.06.2002\" /> The second phase involved renovations to the buildings by 2003, resulting in a two-story extension of the building's wings totaling 190 m\u00b2, 520 covered seatings and other facilities at the grandstand, a more contemporary [[scoreboard]] and a new grass blanket on the football field was laid.<ref name=\"skiveam-stadion\" /><ref name=\"sik-nyh\" /><ref name=\"sik100\" /> The existing [[changing room]]s were renovated with additional changing rooms installed for the referees.<ref name=\"sik-nyh\" /> Changes also included facilities such as an [[Health club|exercise room]], [[public toilet]]s, a [[cafeteria]] with an extended terrace, a [[kitchen]] at the [[Storey#Numbering|building's ground floor]], while the first floor got VIP rooms for sponsors, press and meetings, a speakerbox, and rooms for the local athletics and cycling clubs, Skive AM and Skive Cykelklub.<ref name=\"sik-nyh\" /> Plankings were erected around the stadium as part of the modernisations to the stadium, with the support of Skive IK's then [[chairperson|chairman]], to prevent matches being viewed from Engvej, and the Skive Committee on Culture and Industry took the initiative to beautify the planking with [[vine|climbing plants]].<ref name=\"skifol-forbudt\" />\n\nThe running tracks were renovated again in 2009 due to wear and tear together with the buildings in 2010, and included the installation of a [[balcony]] at the grandstand and, due to security reasons, an designated area for the away fans at association football matches and better sponsor facilities.<ref name=\"skiveam-stadion\" /> On 7 and 10 April 2016, the stadium hosted two [[2016 UEFA Women's Under-19 Championship qualification]] games, and have previously staged two men's [[Exhibition game|friendlies]] for the [[Denmark national football team|Danish national youth teams]] in 1961 and 2015.<ref name=\"ldb-skive\" /> An upgrade of the existing [[floodlight]]s of 150 [[lux]] to 500 lux was done in the late 2000s to better support the minimum requirements of 1000 lux set forward for evening TV-transmissions at level 2.\n\nNew demands for [[under-soil heating]] at all professional matches in the Danish 1st Division were implemented beginning with the 2017/18 season, and Skive IK could no longer rely on a several years long dispensation from the Danish FA. Hence, in the summer of 2017 [[Skive Municipality]] decided to invest DKK 2.6 million in installing a total of 25 kilometers of pipes under the municipal owned facility's football field as part of the new heating system provided by Danjord.<ref name=\"tvmv-varme\" /><ref name=\"sf-28.11.2018\" /> In the years leading up to 2010, both Skive IK Elite A/S and Skive AM had been paying Skive Municipality an [[Economic rent|annual rent]] of DKK 100,000 and in the years leading up to 2019, SIK Elite were paying DKK 318,999 in annual rent for the usage of Skive Stadium, but the latest investments to the ground heating and recent overpayments from Skive IK meant an adjustment of the annual rent down to DKK 295,000 not including the payment for using the new heating system.<ref name=\"sf-28.11.2018\" /> The watering system at the stadium, installed in the summer of 2010, makes use of the nearby river, Karup \u00c5, which lowers the cost of water to a minimum.<ref name=\"sf-26.07.2018\" />\n\n== Name, sponsorships and logos ==\nOn 8 September 2009, the Finance Committee of [[Skive Municipality]] approved the sale of the rights to naming [[sponsor (commercial)|sponsorships]] at Skive Stadium to Skive IK Elite A/S for DKK 25,000 for four years in addition to having the rights to sell banner ads at Skive Stadium.<ref name=\"sf-09.09.2009\" /><ref name=\"sf-14.11.2009\" /> On 1 July 2010 the regional [[bank]], Sparbank, obtained the naming rights for the stadium, renaming it Sparbank Arena, creating matching names with the indoor athletics hall next to the stadium, that was constructed in 2007.<ref name=\"sparbank-05.07.2010\" /> When the regional [[Skive, Denmark|Skive]]-based bank merged with the [[Aalborg]]-based bank [[Spar Nord Bank]] in the fall of 2012, the sponsorship agreement was continued in the new financial constellation, with the stadium name being changed to Spar Nord Arena, beginning 18 November 2012.<ref name=\"sf-19.11.2012\" /> The bank announced a withdrawal from its main sponsorship of Skive IK Elite A/S and its naming rights to the stadium in the fall of 2017, which was made public in February 2018, but would continue having the naming rights for the stadium in 2018 until a new sponsor was found.<ref name=\"bold.dk-21.03.2018\" /><ref name=\"skiveik-26.03.2018\" /> Due to uncertainty surrounding the withdrawal, for a short period in March 2018, the stadium was hence temporarily referred to as SIK Arena.<ref name=\"bold.dk-21.03.2018\" /> On 1 July 2018, Skive Stadium officially changed its name to Hancock Arena, when a sponsorship deal was reached between the local brewery Hancock Bryggerierne A/S and SIK Elite, that is set to expire on 1 January 2022.<ref name=\"bold.dk-19.04.2018\" /> At [[FIFA]] and [[UEFA]] matches, it is still known under its original name, Skive Stadium, due to sponsorship restrictions.\n\nLogos used for the naming rights agreements of the stadium:\n<gallery widths=\"170px\">\nFile:blank.png | '''Sparbank Arena'''<br />(2010\u20132012)<br />Sponsor: Sparbank\nFile:blank.png | '''Spar Nord Arena'''<br />(2012\u20132018)<br />Sponsor: [[Spar Nord Bank]]\nFile:blank.png | '''Hancock Arena'''<br />(2018\u2013''present'')<br />Sponsor: Hancock Brewery\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"skiveik-stadion\">{{cite web |title=Fakta om Hancock Arena |url=http://www.skive-ik.dk/fan/stadion |website=www.skive-ik.dk |publisher=[[Skive IK|Skive Idr\u00e6ts Klub]] |accessdate=14 December 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214131810/http://www.skive-ik.dk/fan/stadion |archivedate=14 December 2019 |language=da}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"sik100\">{{cite book |last1=Preisler |first1=Erik |title=SIK - Skive idr\u00e6tsklub gennem 100 \u00e5r |date=2000 |publisher=Skive Idr\u00e6tsklub |location=Skive |isbn=87-988248-0-5 |pages=42-46; 57-60; 132-133 |language=da |chapter=Nyt stadion; Den lange march mod divisionerne; Stadion eller Egeris}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"bold.dk-19.04.2018\">{{cite news |last1=T\u00f8fting |first1=Nicolai Skovsgaard |title=NordicBet Liga: Stadion i Skive bliver til Hancock Arena |url=https://www.bold.dk/fodbold/nyheder/stadion-i-skive-bliver-til-hancock-arena/ |accessdate=14 December 2019 |publisher=www.bold.dk |date=19 April 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214160746/https://www.bold.dk/fodbold/nyheder/stadion-i-skive-bliver-til-hancock-arena/ |archivedate=14 December 2019 |language=da}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"bold.dk-21.03.2018\">{{cite news |last1=T\u00f8fting |first1=Nicolai Skovsgaard |title=Skive har landet to nye hovedsponsorer |url=https://www.bold.dk/fodbold/nyheder/skive-har-landet-to-nye-hovedsponsorer/