title=Jack Leach \u2013 Squad |publisher=Somerset County Cricket Club |accessdate=30 April 2013 }}</ref> prior to signing a professional contract with Somerset. Leach represented [[Dorset County Cricket Club]] in the 2010 [[Minor Counties Cricket Championship]], and bowled his side to victory in the final against [[Lincolnshire County Cricket Club|Lincolnshire]] taking 6/21 in their second innings.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/266/266298.html |title=Dorset v Lincolnshire in 2010 |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=30 April 2013 }}</ref> Leach completed his degree at the [[University of Wales Institute, Cardiff]] in sports coaching.<ref name=\"MCC University profile\"/> Whilst attending university Leach represented [[Cardiff MCC University|Cardiff MCCU]] in 2011 and 2012 making his first-class debut against his county side Somerset in March 2012, bowling 41 overs but failing to take a wicket as Somerset amassed 642/3[[Declaration and forfeiture|d]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/542465.html |title=Somerset v Cardiff MCCU at Taunton, 31 March \u2013 2 April, 2012 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=30 April 2013 }}</ref>\n\nLeach made his Somerset debut in a two-day match against the [[South African cricket team in England in 2012|touring]] [[South Africa national cricket team|South Africans]] in July 2012, claiming the prized wicket of [[Hashim Amla]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-south-africa-2012/content/story/571791.html |title=Duminy finds valuable form ahead of Tests |last=Moonda |first=Firdose |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=10 July 2012 |accessdate=30 April 2013 }}</ref> He made his first-class debut for Somerset in the [[2012 County Championship]] match against [[Lancashire County Cricket Club|Lancashire]] in August 2012,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thisisbristol.co.uk/Spinner-Leach-lined-Somerset-debut-Liverpool/story-16623597-detail/story.html |title=Spinner Leach is lined up for Somerset debut in Liverpool |publisher=The Bristol Post |date=1 August 2012 |accessdate=30 April 2013 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130505155456/http://www.thisisbristol.co.uk/Spinner-Leach-lined-Somerset-debut-Liverpool/story-16623597-detail/story.html |archive-date=5 May 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> the rain affected match finished as a draw with Leach claiming [[Kyle Hogg]] as his maiden first-class wicket.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2012/content/story/575419.html |title=Prince turns match on its head |last=Hodgson |first=Myles |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=3 August 2012 |accessdate=30 April 2013 }}</ref> Further opportunities in the first team were limited for the rest of the 2012 season with the signing of Pakistani spinner [[Abdur Rehman (cricketer, born 1980)|Abdur Rehman]], and Leach only featured in one further County Championship match and three matches in the [[2012 Clydesdale Bank 40]], but ended the season ninth in the national first-class averages with 12 wickets at 18.83 runs apiece.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.somersetcountycc.co.uk/2012/09/jacks-off-to-play-grade-cricket-in-brisbane/ |title=Jack's off to play Grade Cricket in Brisbane |publisher=Somerset County Cricket Club |date=25 September 2012 |accessdate=30 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920235713/http://www.somersetcountycc.co.uk/2012/09/jacks-off-to-play-grade-cricket-in-brisbane/ |archive-date=20 September 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Leach spent the 2012\u201313 winter playing [[grade cricket]] for [[Valley District Cricket Club]] in [[Brisbane]], Australia, helping his side to win the T20 competition.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.somersetcountycc.co.uk/2013/03/jack-leach-aiming-for-championship-opener-against-durham/ |title=Jack Leach aiming for Championship opener against Durham |publisher=Somerset County Cricket Club |date=24 March 2013 |accessdate=30 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130526212128/http://www.somersetcountycc.co.uk/2013/03/jack-leach-aiming-for-championship-opener-against-durham/ |archive-date=26 May 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nLeach returned to Somerset for pre-season on a summer contract and played his first [[2013 County Championship|Championship]] game of the season against [[Warwickshire County Cricket Club|Warwickshire]] due to an injury to first choice spinner [[George Dockrell]]; he took his maiden five-wicket haul in the second innings, with 24 of his 44 overs being maidens.<ref name=\"Maiden Five-wicket haul\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/22339873 |title=Jack Leach: Somerset spinner frustrated by Bears draw |publisher=BBC Sport |date=30 April 2013 |accessdate=30 April 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nOn 14 February 2018, while playing for the [[England Lions (cricket team)|England Lions]] against [[West Indies A]], Leach achieved match figures of 8-110; in doing so, he beat the previous best figures by an England Lions spinner ([[Graeme Swann]]'s 8-156).<ref>{{cite web|title=Jack Leach claims best figures by England Lions spinner during defeat to West Indies A|url=http://www.skysports.com/cricket/news/12173/11250662/jack-leach-claims-best-figures-by-england-lions-spinner-during-defeat-to-west-indies-a|website=Sky Sports|accessdate=14 February 2018|date=14 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March 2018, he was called up to England's [[Test cricket|Test]] squad for the [[English cricket team in New Zealand in 2017\u201318|tour of New Zealand]] as an injury replacement for [[Mason Crane]].<ref>https://www.telegraph.co.uk/cricket/2018/03/16/england-call-jack-leach-replace-injured-mason-crane/</ref> He made his debut in the second Test in [[Christchurch]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/1115781.html|title=2nd Test, England tour of Australia and New Zealand at Christchurch, Mar 30 - Apr 3 2018|work=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=30 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn an unusual circumstance, with 1 over left to play during [[English cricket team in Sri Lanka in 2018\u201319|a Test match against Sri Lanka]] on 15 November 2018, Leach opened England's innings as a [[nightwatchman (cricket)|nightwatchman]], surviving till stumps. He was dismissed for 1 off 11 balls the next morning.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/18602/commentary/1140386/sri-lanka-vs-england-2nd-test-eng-in-sl-2018-19|title=2nd Test, England tour of Sri Lanka at Kandy, Nov 14-18 2018|work=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=16 November 2018}}</ref> In July 2019, in the one-off Test [[Irish cricket team in England in 2019|against Ireland]], Leach was once again the nightwatchman for England, batting for a single over at the close of day one.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/49114455 |title=England v Ireland: Jack Leach makes 92 before hosts collapse in Lord's Test |work=BBC Sport |accessdate=26 July 2019}}</ref> England won the Test by 143 runs, with Leach scoring 92 runs, which earned him the man of the match award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/series/18774/report/1152839/day/3/england-vs-ireland-only-test-ireland-tour-of-england-2019 |title=Chris Woakes and Stuart Broad wreck Ireland dream in a session |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=26 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe was then recalled for the second Ashes test at [[Lord's|Lords]], on 14 August 2019, where he scored 6 not out in the first innings and took 1-19 and 3-37 in Australia's first and second innings respectively. England drew the match.\n\nLeach scored 1 run in a partnership of 76 with [[Ben Stokes]], to help [[England National Cricket Team|England]] win the third Ashes test at [[Headingley Stadium|Headingley]], by 1 wicket.\n\nLeach gained a cult following over the summer of 2019, with his glasses being a contributing factor. He regularly cleans them through his innings, and has received free Specsavers glasses for life following his heroics supporting Ben Stokes in the dramatic Headingley test.<ref>{{cite web |title=Specsavers to offer England's Jack Leach 'free glasses for life' |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/cricket/specsavers-to-offer-englands-jack-leach-free-glasses-for-life-after-ben-stokes-tweet-a4221241.html |website=Evening Standard |language=en |date=25 August 2019}}</ref> This cult reputation was enhanced by his behaviour off the pitch, such as leading some of the England team out to recreate his famous run at Headingley after the match.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dhingra |first1=Himanshu |title=Watch: Jack Leach recreates that single in 76 run partnership with Ben Stokes |url=https://www.livemint.com/sports/cricket-news/watch-jack-leach-recreates-that-single-in-76-run-partnership-with-ben-stokes-1566920791740.html |website=Mint |language=en |date=27 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of people diagnosed with Crohn's disease]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cricinfo|id=455524}}\n\n{{Somerset County Cricket Club squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leach, Jack}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Taunton]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Cardiff Metropolitan University]]\n[[Category:English cricketers]]\n[[Category:England Test cricketers]]\n[[Category:Dorset cricketers]]\n[[Category:Cardiff MCCU cricketers]]\n[[Category:Somerset cricketers]]\n[[Category:Marylebone Cricket Club cricketers]]\n[[Category:People with Crohn's disease]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jack_Leach"}
{"title_page": "Universit\u00e9 Laval", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n|name         = Universit\u00e9 Laval\n<!-- |native_name  = Universit\u00e9 Laval -->\n|image_name   = Ulaval Shield.svg\n|image_size   = 170px\n|motto        = {{native name|la|Deo favente haud pluribus impar}}\n|mottoeng     = By the grace of God, to no one equal\n|established  = {{start date and age|1663}} ([[S\u00e9minaire de Qu\u00e9bec]])<br />{{start date and age|1852|12|8}} ([[Royal Charter]])\n|type         = [[Public university|Public]]\n|former_names = \n|endowment    = [[Canadian dollar|CAD$]]377 million <ref name=\"ulaval.ca\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ulaval.ca/notre-universite/salle-de-presse/information-institutionnelle/quelques-chiffres.html|title=Quelques chiffres|website=Universit\u00e9 Laval}}</ref>\n|rector       = [[Sophie D'Amours]]\n|city         = [[Quebec City]]\n|state        = [[Quebec]]\n|language     = [[French language|French]]\n|country      = Canada\n|undergrad    = 32,250 <ref name=\"ulaval.ca\"/>\n|postgrad     = 10,750 <ref name=\"ulaval.ca\"/>\n|colours      = Red and Gold {{color box|#FF0000}} {{color box|#FDD017}}\n|staff        = \n|campus       = [[Urban area|Urban]]/[[Suburb]]an\n|free_label   = \n|free         =\n|athletics    = [[Canadian Interuniversity Sport|CIS]] \u2013 [[Quebec Student Sport Federation|RSEQ]]\n|nickname     = [[Laval Rouge-et-Or|Rouge-et-Or]]\n|affiliations = [[Association of Universities and Colleges of Canada|AUCC]], [[Canadian Association of Research Libraries|CARL]], [[International Association of Universities|IAU]], [[L'Association des universit\u00e9s de la francophonie canadienne|AUFC]], [[University of the Arctic|UArctic]], [[Association of Commonwealth Universities|ACU]], [[Canadian Interuniversity Sport|CIS]], [[Quebec Student Sports Federation|QSSF]], [[Canadian Bureau for International Education|CBIE]], [[U15 Group of Canadian Research Universities|U15]]\n|website      = [https://www.ulaval.ca/ www.ulaval.ca]\n|logo         = Ulaval Logo.svg\n}}\n\n'''Universit\u00e9 Laval''' is a [[French-language]], [[Public university|public]] [[research university]] in [[Quebec City]], [[Quebec]], [[Canada]]. The University was founded by [[royal charter]] issued by [[Queen Victoria]] in 1852, with roots in the founding of the [[S\u00e9minaire de Qu\u00e9bec]] in 1663 by [[Fran\u00e7ois de Laval|Fran\u00e7ois de Montmorency-Laval]], making it the oldest centre of higher education in Canada and the first North American institution to offer higher education in French. The university, whose campus was erected from the 1950s onward in the suburban borough of [[Sainte-Foy\u2013Sillery\u2013Cap-Rouge]], is ranked among the top 10 Canadian universities in terms of research funding<ref>Universit\u00e9 Laval. [http://www.scom.ulaval.ca/Presentation/anglais/background.html \"Universit\u00e9 Laval at a Glance\"]. (accessed 17 April 2007)</ref> and holds 4 Canada Excellence Research Chairs. Like most institutions in Quebec, the name (Universit\u00e9 Laval) is not translated in English.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Fran\u00e7ois de Laval - Project Gutenberg eText 17174.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Fran\u00e7ois de Laval]] \n[[File:The Seminary, Quebec.jpg|thumb|The Seminary, painting, 1886]]\n\nThe university's beginnings go back to 1663 with the founding of the Grand [[S\u00e9minaire de Qu\u00e9bec]] and 1668 with the founding of the Petit S\u00e9minaire by [[Fran\u00e7ois de Laval|Fran\u00e7ois de Montmorency-Laval]], a member of the [[House of Laval]] and the first [[Bishop of New France]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gutenberg.org/files/32699/32699-h/32699-h.htm|title=The Project Gutenberg eBook of The Makers of Canada: Index and Dictionary of Canadian History, Edited by Lawrence Johnstone Burpee and Arthur G. Doughty.|publisher=|accessdate=28 August 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"pc.gc.ca\">https://www.pc.gc.ca/apps/dfhd/page_nhs_eng.aspx?id=694, Qu\u00e9bec Seminary National Historic Site of Canada, Government of Canada</ref>\n\nDuring the French Regime the institution mainly trained priests to serve in [[New France]]. After the [[Conquest of 1760]], the British expanded education in Canada to include the liberal arts. French Canadians had at the time no opportunity to pursue higher education, and [[Ignace Bourget|Bishop Bourget]] of Montreal suggested expanding the S\u00e9minaire de Qu\u00e9bec into Universit\u00e9 Laval. [[Louis-Jacques Casault|Louis Casault]], a priest who taught physics at the S\u00e9minaire de Qu\u00e9bec, went to Europe to seek a royal charter and study the best university systems there.\n\nThe S\u00e9minaire de Qu\u00e9bec was granted a royal charter on December 8, 1852, by [[Victoria of the United Kingdom|Queen Victoria]], at the request of [[James Bruce, 8th Earl of Elgin|Lord Elgin]] (Governor-General of the Province of Canada), creating Universit\u00e9 Laval with \"the rights and privileges of a university\".<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/index.cfm?PgNm=TCE&Params=U1ARTU0001990 Laval University/Universit\u00e9 Laval<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070816195903/http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/index.cfm?PgNm=TCE&Params=U1ARTU0001990 |date=2007-08-16 }}</ref> The charter was signed in 1852. [[Pope Benedict XV]] approved the plan and authorized the institution to establish chairs of theology and confer degrees.<ref>[http://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/6466.mobile The Project Gutenberg EBook #6466 of 'The Intellectual Development of the Canadian People, A historical review' by John George Bourinot, House of Commons, Ottawa, February 17th, 1881]</ref>\n[[File:Grand-S\u00e9minaire-Qu\u00e9bec.jpg|thumb|left|225px|left|The Old S\u00e9minaire de Qu\u00e9bec in 2008]]\nIn 1878, the university opened a second campus in [[Montreal]], which became the [[Universit\u00e9 de Montr\u00e9al]] on May 8, 1919, by a writ of [[Pope Benedict XV]]. In 1971, a second charter transferred all authority to the Universit\u00e9 Laval council.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nBy 1925, the university had outgrown its location. The Old City was very crowded, making it difficult to add new buildings to the campus. The university moved to [[Sainte-Foy, Quebec City|Sainte-Foy]] in the 1950s, which at the time was a semi-rural community west of the Quebec city centre. The School of Architecture returned to the old building (now affectionately referred to as ''Le Vieux S\u00e9minaire'') in 1989.\n\nUniversit\u00e9 Laval is governed by a board of governors and a faculty senate. This structure was modelled on the provincial University of Toronto Act of 1906, which established a bicameral system of university government consisting of a senate (faculty), responsible for academic policy, and a board of governors (citizens) exercising exclusive control over financial policy and having formal authority in all other matters. The president, appointed by the board, was to serve as a link between the two bodies and lead the institution.<ref name=langton1906>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/universitytoron02macagoog|page=[https://archive.org/details/universitytoron02macagoog/page/n394 306]|title=The University of Toronto and its colleges, 1827-1906|last=Langton|first=Hugh Hornby|last2=Macallum|first2=Archibald Byron|publisher=The University Library, pub. by the librarian|year=1906}}</ref>{{rp|306}}\n\nIn the early part of the 20th century, the need for higher education expanded beyond the classical fields of theology, law and medicine, and the university introduced science and social-science departments such as forestry and household science.<ref name=langton1906 />{{rp|1904}} In addition, graduate training based on the German-inspired American model of specialized course work and the completion of a research thesis was introduced.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n\"Laval\", a waltz by French-Canadian ragtime composer, [[Wilfrid Beaudry]], was dedicated to the students at Laval University and the University of Montreal. The music for piano was published in Qu\u00e9bec by J. Beaudry, circa 1906.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://collectionscanada.gc.ca/ourl/res.php?url_ver=Z39.88-2004&url_tim=2016-07-01T18%3A38%3A44Z&url_ctx_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&rft_dat=16182129&rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fcollectionscanada.gc.ca%3Aamicus&lang=eng |title= Laval |newspaper=Amicus.collectionscanada.gc.ca |date=1906  |author=Wilfrid Beaudry |accessdate= July 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1929, the Qu\u00e9bec Seminary was designated as a national historic site of Canada.<ref name=\"pc.gc.ca\"/>\n\nThe university opened its department of social, political, and economic sciences in 1938, signalling a change of approach that continued into the 1960s, based on an idea of higher education as the key to social justice and economic productivity for individuals and society.<ref>Behiels, Michael, \"Le p\u00e8re Georges-Henri L\u00e9vesque et l'\u00e9tablissement des sciences sociales \u00e0 Laval: 1938\u20131955\", Revue de l'Universit\u00e9 d'Ottawa 52, no. 3 (juil.-sept. 1982). Appears in English translation in \"Youth, University, and Canadian Society\", edited by Paul Axelrod and John G. Reid. Kingston and Montreal: McGill-Queen's University of Press, 1989.</ref>\n\nThe royal charter that founded Universit\u00e9 Laval in 1852 was designated a National Historic Event in 1972.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pc.gc.ca/apps/dfhd/page_nhs_eng.aspx?id=1365 |title=Founding of Universit\u00e9 Laval National Historic Event |publisher=Parks Canada|website=Directory of Federal Heritage Designations|accessdate=March 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThis location, at 1 Rempart Street, Qu\u00e9bec, still continues operation as a centre for educating Roman Catholic priests. A section of the Vieux S\u00e9minaire has been the location for the Universit\u00e9's school of architecture since 1987.<ref name=\"pc.gc.ca\"/><ref>https://www.ville.quebec.qc.ca/en/citoyens/patrimoine/quartiers/vieux_quebec/interet/seminaire_de_quebec.aspx, S\u00c9MINAIRE DE QU\u00c9BEC, Ville de Qu\u00e9bec</ref> The Camille-Roy pavilion houses the restored Promotions Room which can be rented as a venue for various types of events.<ref>https://www.quebec-cite.com/en/businesses/attractions/heritage-sites/religious-sites/seminaire-de-quebec/,  S\u00e9minaire de Qu\u00e9bec, Ville de Qu\u00e9bec</ref>\n\nIn 2017, the university became the first in Canada to divest its endowment from fossil fuel-related companies.<ref>https://www.mcgilltribune.com/news/universite-laval-first-university-in-canada-to-divest-from-fossil-fuels-989800/</ref>\n\n==Buildings and features==\nAfter it was granted a university charter, several buildings were built in Old Quebec, including the School of Chemistry (1923), the addition on Ste. Famille Street (1931), the Mining School (1938), and the cafeteria building (1945), all by architect Joseph Simeon Bergeron.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionaryofarchitectsincanada.org/node/1103|title=Bergeron, Joseph Simeon|publisher=|accessdate=2 November 2018}}</ref> However, the neighborhood was already crowded and activities later moved in nearby Sainte-Foy, which was more spacious.\n\n===Campus building===\nToday's campus covers {{cvt|1.2|km2}} and has over 30 buildings (also called ''pavillons''), including many iconic exemplars of [[modern architecture]]. Its earliest buildings and landscapes were designed by [[Edouard Fiset]] ([[:fr:\u00c9douard Fiset|fr]]) from the 1950s, and of its lands, 56 percent are wooded areas, grasslands, and sports fields{{citation needed|date=November 2018}} .\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nPavillon Ferdinand Vandry.jpg|Ferdinand Vandry Pavilion, hosting health sciences faculties\nPavillon Adrien-Pouliot.jpg|''L'Homme devant la Science'' (1963), mural by [[Jordi Bonet]] on Adrien-Pouliot Hall\nBibliothequeulaval.jpg|Social science library building\nPavillon Palasis-Prince - Universit\u00e9 -Laval - Quebec City - October 2007.jpg|Palasis-Prince building (administrative sciences)\nPavillon Charles-De Koninck 2016.jpg|Pavillon Charles-De Koninck (social sciences and law)\nAbitibiprice.jpg|Abitibi-Price building (forestry, geography and geomatics)\nPavillon Gene-H.-Kruger.jpg|Gene-H.-Kruger building (wood research)\nPavillons FAS et SDE.JPG|''F\u00e9lix-Antoine-Savard'' and educational sciences buildings\nULaval campus.jpg|Western end of the campus\n</gallery>\n\n===Other infrastructure===\nPractically all buildings are linked by {{cvt|10|km}} of underground walkways, which are particularly useful in the winter and whose walls are mostly covered by murals painted by student associations and student visitors over the years, as well as graffiti. The campus is also home to the ''Roger-Van den Hende'' botanical garden ([[:fr:Jardin universitaire Roger-Van den Hende|fr]]) which contains some 67 species of deciduous and coniferous trees and 60 different species of birds. The Louis-Jacques-Casault building also hosts the regional branch of the [[Biblioth\u00e8que et Archives nationales du Qu\u00e9bec|National Archives of Quebec]]. The sport building is called [[PEPS]] and is said to be the largest sport complex in eastern Canada.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.quebecoriginal.com/en-ca/listing/things-to-do/sports-and-nature/skating-rinks/pavillon-de-leducation-physique-et-des-sports-peps-universite-laval-230331533 |title=Pavillon de l'\u00c9ducation physique et des sports (PEPS) (Universit\u00e9 Laval) |website=Qu\u00e9bec Original |access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref> It is adjacent to the covered TELUS stadium ([[:fr:Stade TELUS-Universit\u00e9 Laval|fr]]).\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nTunnel ULaval Peps.jpg|Pedestrian [[tunnel]]\nVandenHende WG.jpg|Water Garden at ''Roger-Van den Hende'' botanical garden\nPavillon Louis-Jacques-Casault 1.jpg|A branch of the National Archives is found in Pavillon Casault\nLaval University PEPS 03.jpg|Olympic swimming pool inside the PEPS complex\nTelus Stadium, Laval University.jpg|[[TELUS]] stadium\n</gallery>\n\n===Off campus===\nApart from the school of architecture, located in [[Old Quebec]] since 1988,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.arc.ulaval.ca/a-propos/historique.html |title=Historique - \u00c9cole d'architecture |website=Universit\u00e9 Laval |language=fr-FR |access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref> the only out of campus facilities are the school of visual arts in the downtown neighborhood of [[Saint-Roch (Quebec City)|Saint-Roch's]], and the experimental [[Montmorency forest]] ([[:fr:For\u00eat Montmorency|fr]]) ({{cvt|70|km}} north of Quebec City). \n<gallery class=\"center\">\nForet Montmorency - 055.jpg|A facility of the experimental forest\n\u00c9cole architecture ULaval.JPG|The school of architecture\nLa Fabrique - 01.jpg|''La Fabrique'' building hosts the school of art\n</gallery>\n\n==Programs==\nAs of 2002, Universit\u00e9 Laval offered over 350 programs to more than 38,000 students. The university also attracts more than 2,500 foreign students annually, and has almost 1,000 students drawn from Canadian provinces outside of Quebec. Many students come to the university for the ''Fran\u00e7ais pour non-francophones'' program that offers instruction in French as a second language to students from Canada and around the world. It is also the only university in Quebec which trains forestry engineers.{{citation needed|date=July 2016}} Since the mid-1980s, Universit\u00e9 Laval has offered distance learning; over 30 programs and 400 courses are offered by distance learning, of which 80% are accessible from the internet.\n\n==Faculties and schools==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=35em|\n* Administrative Sciences\n* [[Agriculture]] and [[Food science]]s<small>*</small>\n* [[Architecture]], [[Urban planning]] and [[Visual arts]]\n* [[Dentistry]]\n* Education\n* [[Facult\u00e9 de droit (Universit\u00e9 Laval)|Facult\u00e9 de Droit]] (Faculty of Law)\n* Facult\u00e9 des Lettres (Humanities)\n* [[Forestry]], [[Geography]] and [[Geomatics]]<small>**</small>\n* Hautes \u00c9tudes Internationales (HEI)\n* Arts\n* [[Universit\u00e9 Laval Facult\u00e9 de m\u00e9decine|Medicine]]\n* [[Music]]\n* [[Nursing]]\n* [[Pharmacy]]\n* [[Philosophy]]\n* Postgraduate Studies\n* Science and Engineering\n* Social Sciences\n* Theology and Religious Studies\n<small>*</small><small> The D\u00e9partement des Sciences des Aliments et de Nutrition has an accredited dietetic program. The university is accredited by a professional organization such as the [[Dietitians of Canada]] and the university's graduates may subsequently become registered dietitians.</small><br />\n<small>**</small><small> The Faculty is part of the [[Association of University Forestry Schools of Canada|AUFSC]] and has accredited baccalaureate of science programs with specializations in forestry & environmental management; forestry operations (co-op) and forestry engineering.</small>\n}}\n\n{{Canadian university rankings\n| UniName = Universit\u00e9 Laval\n| ARWU_W = 201\u2013300\n| ARWU_CAN = 10\u201312\n| THES_W = 251\u2013300\n| THES_N = 11\u201314\n| QS_W = 416\n| QS_N = 15\n| USNWR_GU = 315\n| USNWR_N = 13\n| MAC_med = 12\n| MAC_rep = 15\n|}}\n\n==Research==\nQu\u00e9bec university holds four of the 19 Canada Excellence Research Chairs awarded nationwide: Canada Excellence Research Chair in Remote Sensing of Canada's New Arctic Frontier, Canada Research Excellence Chair in the Microbiome-Endocannabinoidome Axis in Metabolic Health, Canada Excellence Research Chair in Photonic Innovations, and Communication and Canada Excellence Research Chair in Neurophotonics.<ref>{{cite web|title=Canada Excellence Research Chairs|url=http://www.cerc.gc.ca/chairholders-titulaires/index-eng.aspx|website=www.cerc.gc.ca|accessdate=March 29, 2017|language=en|date=2012-11-29}}</ref> The university has also received research funding from [[Huawei]] but has kept the details of the funding confidential.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/huawei-academic-funding-in-canada-1.5372310|title=Huawei funds $56M in academic research in Canada. That has some experts concerned|last=Armstrong|first=Peter|date=November 29, 2019|work=[[CBC News]]|access-date=December 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nationalpost.com/news/canadian-governments-give-huawei-millions-in-funding-while-debate-rages-over-its-5g-role|title=Canadian governments give Huawei millions in funding while debate rages over its 5G role|last=Blackwell|first=Tom|date=February 3, 2020|work=[[National Post]]|access-date=February 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==University press==\n''Les Presses de l'Universit\u00e9 Laval'', which was founded in 1950, deals with Canadian civilization, literature, medieval studies, law, social sciences, physical sciences and engineering.<ref>[http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/index.cfm?PgNm=TCE&Params=A1ARTA0008267 University Presses<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608081406/http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/index.cfm?PgNm=TCE&Params=A1ARTA0008267 |date=2011-06-08 }}</ref>  It publishes some 120 book per year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pulaval.com/a-propos |title=Presses de l'Universit\u00e9 Laval - Editeur de livres universitaires |publisher=Pulaval.com |date= |accessdate=2018-07-16}}</ref>\n\n==University cooperative==\n{{Main|Zone Coop\u00e9rative de l'Universit\u00e9 Laval}}\nThe ''Coop\u00e9rative de l'Universit\u00e9 Laval'' is engaged in the sale of products to customers throughout the university, such as books, lecture notes and computers.\n\n==Athletics and sports teams==\n{{Main|Laval Rouge et Or}}\n[[File:RTEmagicC logo-Rouge-et-Or png.png|185px|thumb|right|Universit\u00e9 Laval Rouge et Or Logo]] Athletics take place at the [[PEPS|PEPS complex]]. Laval's varsity sports teams are named the [[Laval Rouge-et-Or|Rouge-et-Or]] (Red & Gold). As of 2017, the men's [[Laval Rouge et Or football|football team of Laval]] have won nine [[Vanier Cup]]s since 2003 and has thus the most titles in the country, followed by the [[Western Mustangs football|Western Mustangs]] (6 Vanier Cups).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.tsn.ca/western-s-marshall-hoping-to-end-vanier-cup-drought-on-saturday-against-laval-1.925111 |title=Western's Marshall hoping to win first Vanier Cup  |date=2017-11-24 |website=TSN |access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n{{Main| List of Universit\u00e9 Laval people }}\nPublic figures, including Prime Ministers of Canada, Premiers of Quebec, Supreme Court Justices, federal Cabinet Ministers, Senators, and Lieutenant-Governors as well as national and international athletes have graduated from l'Universit\u00e9 Laval. Some of the more prominent are:\n* [[List of prime ministers of Canada|Prime Ministers of Canada]]: [[Louis St. Laurent]], [[Brian Mulroney]] and [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]]\n* [[List of premiers of Quebec|Premiers of Quebec]]: [[Lucien Bouchard]], [[Pierre-Joseph-Olivier Chauveau]], [[Edmund James Flynn]], [[Jean Lesage]], [[Ren\u00e9 L\u00e9vesque]], [[Pauline Marois]], [[Simon-Napol\u00e9on Parent]] and [[Louis-Alexandre Taschereau]]\n* [[List of Justices of the Supreme Court of Canada|Supreme Court Justices]]: [[Suzanne C\u00f4t\u00e9]], [[Louis LeBel]], [[Claire L'Heureux-Dub\u00e9]], [[Charles Fitzpatrick]], [[Arthur Cyrille Albert Malouin]], [[Lawrence Arthur Dumoulin Cannon]], [[Louis-Philippe Pigeon]], [[Julien Chouinard]], [[Robert Taschereau]], [[Henri-Elz\u00e9ar Taschereau]], [[Thibaudeau Rinfret]]\n\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nGrand Duke Jean 29.09.2006.jpg|[[Jean, Grand Duke of Luxembourg|Jean]], [[Monarchy of Luxembourg|Grand Duke of Luxembourg]].\nLouisstlaurent.jpg|[[Louis St. Laurent]], [[List of Canadian Prime Ministers|12th]] [[Prime Minister of Canada]]. \nMulroney.jpg|[[Brian Mulroney]], 18th Prime Minister of Canada.\nJean Chr\u00e9tien 2010.jpg|[[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]], 20th Prime Mininister of Canada.\nJacques-\u00c9douard Alexis.jpg|[[Jacques-\u00c9douard Alexis]], [[List of Prime Ministers of Haiti|9th]] [[Prime Minister of Haiti]].\nNiklaus Wirth, UrGU.jpg|[[Niklaus Wirth]], designer of several programming languages.\nCharles Fitzpatrick.jpg|[[Charles Fitzpatrick]], 5th [[Chief Justice of Canada]]. \n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of universities in Quebec]]\n* [[List of universities in Canada]]\n* [[Group of Thirteen (Canadian universities)]]\n* [[Laval Thomism]]\n* [[List of oldest universities in continuous operation#Oldest Universities by Region (post 1500)|List of oldest universities by region]]\n* [[Quebec City]]\n* [[Canadian university scientific research organizations]]\n* [[Higher education in Quebec]]\n* [[CHYZ|CHYZ campus radio station]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Universit\u00e9 Laval}}\n* [https://www.ulaval.ca/ Official website]\n* [http://www.bibl.ulaval.ca/ Biblioth\u00e8que de l'Universit\u00e9 Laval]\n* [https://www2.ulaval.ca/en/about-the-foundation.html/ Universit\u00e9 Laval Foundation]\n* [https://www2.ulaval.ca/en/academics/faculties-departments-and-schools/forestry-geography-and-geomatics.html/ Faculty of Forestry, Georgraphy and Geomatics]\n* {{CathEncy|wstitle=Laval University of Quebec|short=x}}\n* {{Cite NSRW|wstitle=Laval University|short=x}}\n\n{{Universit\u00e9 Laval}}\n{{Quebec City}}\n{{U15}}\n{{Qc_Uni}}\n{{ShadUni}}\n{{Universities in Canada}}\n{{Canadian law schools}}\n{{Coord|46|46|48|N|71|16|29|W|type:edu|display=title}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Laval, Universite}}\n[[Category:1663 establishments in the French colonial empire]]\n[[Category:1852 establishments in Canada]]\n[[Category:Education in Quebec City]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in the 1660s]]\n[[Category:Forestry education]]\n[[Category:Universit\u00e9 Laval| ]]\n[[Category:Universities in Quebec]]\n[[Category:Higher education in Canada]]\n[[Category:U15 Group of Canadian Research Universities|Laval]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university\n|name         = Universit\u00e9 Laval\n<!-- |native_name  = Universit\u00e9 Laval -->\n|image_name   = Ulaval Shield.svg\n|image_size   = 170px\n|motto        = {{native name|la|Deo favente haud pluribus impar}}\n|mottoeng     = By the grace of God, to no one equal\n|established  = {{start date and age|1663}} ([[S\u00e9minaire de Qu\u00e9bec]])<br />{{start date and age|1852|12|8}} ([[Royal Charter]])\n|type         = [[Public university|Public]]\n|former_names = \n|endowment    = [[Canadian dollar|CAD$]]377 million <ref name=\"ulaval.ca\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ulaval.ca/notre-universite/salle-de-presse/information-institutionnelle/quelques-chiffres.html|title=Quelques chiffres|website=Universit\u00e9 Laval}}</ref>\n|rector       = [[Sophie D'Amours]]\n|city         = [[Quebec City]]\n|state        = [[Quebec]]\n|language     = [[French language|French]]\n|country      = Canada\n|undergrad    = 32,250 <ref name=\"ulaval.ca\"/>\n|postgrad     = 10,750 <ref name=\"ulaval.ca\"/>\n|colours      = Red and Gold {{color box|#FF0000}} {{color box|#FDD017}}\n|staff        = \n|campus       = [[Urban area|Urban]]/[[Suburb]]an\n|free_label   = \n|free         =\n|athletics    = [[Canadian Interuniversity Sport|CIS]] \u2013 [[Quebec Student Sport Federation|RSEQ]]\n|nickname     = [[Laval Rouge-et-Or|Rouge-et-Or]]\n|affiliations = [[Association of Universities and Colleges of Canada|AUCC]], [[Canadian Association of Research Libraries|CARL]], [[International Association of Universities|IAU]], [[L'Association des universit\u00e9s de la francophonie canadienne|AUFC]], [[University of the Arctic|UArctic]], [[Association of Commonwealth Universities|ACU]], [[Canadian Interuniversity Sport|CIS]], [[Quebec Student Sports Federation|QSSF]], [[Canadian Bureau for International Education|CBIE]], [[U15 Group of Canadian Research Universities|U15]]\n|website      = [https://www.ulaval.ca/ www.ulaval.ca]\n|logo         = Ulaval Logo.svg\n}}\n\n'''Universit\u00e9 Laval''' is a [[French-language]], public [[research university]] in [[Quebec City]], [[Quebec]], [[Canada]]. The University was founded by [[royal charter]] issued by [[Queen Victoria]] in 1852, with roots in the founding of the [[S\u00e9minaire de Qu\u00e9bec]] in 1663 by [[Fran\u00e7ois de Laval|Fran\u00e7ois de Montmorency-Laval]], making it the oldest centre of higher education in Canada and the first North American institution to offer higher education in French. The university, whose campus was erected from the 1950s onward in the suburban borough of [[Sainte-Foy\u2013Sillery\u2013Cap-Rouge]], is ranked among the top 10 Canadian universities in terms of research funding<ref>Universit\u00e9 Laval. [http://www.scom.ulaval.ca/Presentation/anglais/background.html \"Universit\u00e9 Laval at a Glance\"]. (accessed 17 April 2007)</ref> and holds 4 Canada Excellence Research Chairs. Like most institutions in Quebec, the name (Universit\u00e9 Laval) is not translated in English.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Fran\u00e7ois de Laval - Project Gutenberg eText 17174.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Fran\u00e7ois de Laval]] \n[[File:The Seminary, Quebec.jpg|thumb|The Seminary, painting, 1886]]\n\nThe university's beginnings go back to 1663 with the founding of the Grand [[S\u00e9minaire de Qu\u00e9bec]] and 1668 with the founding of the Petit S\u00e9minaire by [[Fran\u00e7ois de Laval|Fran\u00e7ois de Montmorency-Laval]], a member of the [[House of Laval]] and the first [[Bishop of New France]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gutenberg.org/files/32699/32699-h/32699-h.htm|title=The Project Gutenberg eBook of The Makers of Canada: Index and Dictionary of Canadian History, Edited by Lawrence Johnstone Burpee and Arthur G. Doughty.|publisher=|accessdate=28 August 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"pc.gc.ca\">https://www.pc.gc.ca/apps/dfhd/page_nhs_eng.aspx?id=694, Qu\u00e9bec Seminary National Historic Site of Canada, Government of Canada</ref>\n\nDuring the French Regime the institution mainly trained priests to serve in [[New France]]. After the [[Conquest of 1760]], the British expanded education in Canada to include the liberal arts. French Canadians had at the time no opportunity to pursue higher education, and [[Ignace Bourget|Bishop Bourget]] of Montreal suggested expanding the S\u00e9minaire de Qu\u00e9bec into Universit\u00e9 Laval. [[Louis-Jacques Casault|Louis Casault]], a priest who taught physics at the S\u00e9minaire de Qu\u00e9bec, went to Europe to seek a royal charter and study the best university systems there.\n\nThe S\u00e9minaire de Qu\u00e9bec was granted a royal charter on December 8, 1852, by [[Victoria of the United Kingdom|Queen Victoria]], at the request of [[James Bruce, 8th Earl of Elgin|Lord Elgin]] (Governor-General of the Province of Canada), creating Universit\u00e9 Laval with \"the rights and privileges of a university\".<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/index.cfm?PgNm=TCE&Params=U1ARTU0001990 Laval University/Universit\u00e9 Laval<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070816195903/http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/index.cfm?PgNm=TCE&Params=U1ARTU0001990 |date=2007-08-16 }}</ref> The charter was signed in 1852. [[Pope Benedict XV]] approved the plan and authorized the institution to establish chairs of theology and confer degrees.<ref>[http://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/6466.mobile The Project Gutenberg EBook #6466 of 'The Intellectual Development of the Canadian People, A historical review' by John George Bourinot, House of Commons, Ottawa, February 17th, 1881]</ref>\n[[File:Grand-S\u00e9minaire-Qu\u00e9bec.jpg|thumb|left|225px|left|The Old S\u00e9minaire de Qu\u00e9bec in 2008]]\nIn 1878, the university opened a second campus in [[Montreal]], which became the [[Universit\u00e9 de Montr\u00e9al]] on May 8, 1919, by a writ of [[Pope Benedict XV]]. In 1971, a second charter transferred all authority to the Universit\u00e9 Laval council.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nBy 1925, the university had outgrown its location. The Old City was very crowded, making it difficult to add new buildings to the campus. The university moved to [[Sainte-Foy, Quebec City|Sainte-Foy]] in the 1950s, which at the time was a semi-rural community west of the Quebec city centre. The School of Architecture returned to the old building (now affectionately referred to as ''Le Vieux S\u00e9minaire'') in 1989.\n\nUniversit\u00e9 Laval is governed by a board of governors and a faculty senate. This structure was modelled on the provincial University of Toronto Act of 1906, which established a bicameral system of university government consisting of a senate (faculty), responsible for academic policy, and a board of governors (citizens) exercising exclusive control over financial policy and having formal authority in all other matters. The president, appointed by the board, was to serve as a link between the two bodies and lead the institution.<ref name=langton1906>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/universitytoron02macagoog|page=[https://archive.org/details/universitytoron02macagoog/page/n394 306]|title=The University of Toronto and its colleges, 1827-1906|last=Langton|first=Hugh Hornby|last2=Macallum|first2=Archibald Byron|publisher=The University Library, pub. by the librarian|year=1906}}</ref>{{rp|306}}\n\nIn the early part of the 20th century, the need for higher education expanded beyond the classical fields of theology, law and medicine, and the university introduced science and social-science departments such as forestry and household science.<ref name=langton1906 />{{rp|1904}} In addition, graduate training based on the German-inspired American model of specialized course work and the completion of a research thesis was introduced.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n\"Laval\", a waltz by French-Canadian ragtime composer, [[Wilfrid Beaudry]], was dedicated to the students at Laval University and the University of Montreal. The music for piano was published in Qu\u00e9bec by J. Beaudry, circa 1906.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://collectionscanada.gc.ca/ourl/res.php?url_ver=Z39.88-2004&url_tim=2016-07-01T18%3A38%3A44Z&url_ctx_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&rft_dat=16182129&rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fcollectionscanada.gc.ca%3Aamicus&lang=eng |title= Laval |newspaper=Amicus.collectionscanada.gc.ca |date=1906  |author=Wilfrid Beaudry |accessdate= July 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1929, the Qu\u00e9bec Seminary was designated as a national historic site of Canada.<ref name=\"pc.gc.ca\"/>\n\nThe university opened its department of social, political, and economic sciences in 1938, signalling a change of approach that continued into the 1960s, based on an idea of higher education as the key to social justice and economic productivity for individuals and society.<ref>Behiels, Michael, \"Le p\u00e8re Georges-Henri L\u00e9vesque et l'\u00e9tablissement des sciences sociales \u00e0 Laval: 1938\u20131955\", Revue de l'Universit\u00e9 d'Ottawa 52, no. 3 (juil.-sept. 1982). Appears in English translation in \"Youth, University, and Canadian Society\", edited by Paul Axelrod and John G. Reid. Kingston and Montreal: McGill-Queen's University of Press, 1989.</ref>\n\nThe royal charter that founded Universit\u00e9 Laval in 1852 was designated a National Historic Event in 1972.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pc.gc.ca/apps/dfhd/page_nhs_eng.aspx?id=1365 |title=Founding of Universit\u00e9 Laval National Historic Event |publisher=Parks Canada|website=Directory of Federal Heritage Designations|accessdate=March 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThis location, at 1 Rempart Street, Qu\u00e9bec, still continues operation as a centre for educating Roman Catholic priests. A section of the Vieux S\u00e9minaire has been the location for the Universit\u00e9's school of architecture since 1987.<ref name=\"pc.gc.ca\"/><ref>https://www.ville.quebec.qc.ca/en/citoyens/patrimoine/quartiers/vieux_quebec/interet/seminaire_de_quebec.aspx, S\u00c9MINAIRE DE QU\u00c9BEC, Ville de Qu\u00e9bec</ref> The Camille-Roy pavilion houses the restored Promotions Room which can be rented as a venue for various types of events.<ref>https://www.quebec-cite.com/en/businesses/attractions/heritage-sites/religious-sites/seminaire-de-quebec/,  S\u00e9minaire de Qu\u00e9bec, Ville de Qu\u00e9bec</ref>\n\nIn 2017, the university became the first in Canada to divest its endowment from fossil fuel-related companies.<ref>https://www.mcgilltribune.com/news/universite-laval-first-university-in-canada-to-divest-from-fossil-fuels-989800/</ref>\n\n==Buildings and features==\nAfter it was granted a university charter, several buildings were built in Old Quebec, including the School of Chemistry (1923), the addition on Ste. Famille Street (1931), the Mining School (1938), and the cafeteria building (1945), all by architect Joseph Simeon Bergeron.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionaryofarchitectsincanada.org/node/1103|title=Bergeron, Joseph Simeon|publisher=|accessdate=2 November 2018}}</ref> However, the neighborhood was already crowded and activities later moved in nearby Sainte-Foy, which was more spacious.\n\n===Campus building===\nToday's campus covers {{cvt|1.2|km2}} and has over 30 buildings (also called ''pavillons''), including many iconic exemplars of [[modern architecture]]. Its earliest buildings and landscapes were designed by [[Edouard Fiset]] ([[:fr:\u00c9douard Fiset|fr]]) from the 1950s, and of its lands, 56 percent are wooded areas, grasslands, and sports fields{{citation needed|date=November 2018}} .\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nPavillon Ferdinand Vandry.jpg|Ferdinand Vandry Pavilion, hosting health sciences faculties\nPavillon Adrien-Pouliot.jpg|''L'Homme devant la Science'' (1963), mural by [[Jordi Bonet]] on Adrien-Pouliot Hall\nBibliothequeulaval.jpg|Social science library building\nPavillon Palasis-Prince - Universit\u00e9 -Laval - Quebec City - October 2007.jpg|Palasis-Prince building (administrative sciences)\nPavillon Charles-De Koninck 2016.jpg|Pavillon Charles-De Koninck (social sciences and law)\nAbitibiprice.jpg|Abitibi-Price building (forestry, geography and geomatics)\nPavillon Gene-H.-Kruger.jpg|Gene-H.-Kruger building (wood research)\nPavillons FAS et SDE.JPG|''F\u00e9lix-Antoine-Savard'' and educational sciences buildings\nULaval campus.jpg|Western end of the campus\n</gallery>\n\n===Other infrastructure===\nPractically all buildings are linked by {{cvt|10|km}} of underground walkways, which are particularly useful in the winter and whose walls are mostly covered by murals painted by student associations and student visitors over the years, as well as graffiti. The campus is also home to the ''Roger-Van den Hende'' botanical garden ([[:fr:Jardin universitaire Roger-Van den Hende|fr]]) which contains some 67 species of deciduous and coniferous trees and 60 different species of birds. The Louis-Jacques-Casault building also hosts the regional branch of the [[Biblioth\u00e8que et Archives nationales du Qu\u00e9bec|National Archives of Quebec]]. The sport building is called [[PEPS]] and is said to be the largest sport complex in eastern Canada.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.quebecoriginal.com/en-ca/listing/things-to-do/sports-and-nature/skating-rinks/pavillon-de-leducation-physique-et-des-sports-peps-universite-laval-230331533 |title=Pavillon de l'\u00c9ducation physique et des sports (PEPS) (Universit\u00e9 Laval) |website=Qu\u00e9bec Original |access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref> It is adjacent to the covered TELUS stadium ([[:fr:Stade TELUS-Universit\u00e9 Laval|fr]]).\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nTunnel ULaval Peps.jpg|Pedestrian [[tunnel]]\nVandenHende WG.jpg|Water Garden at ''Roger-Van den Hende'' botanical garden\nPavillon Louis-Jacques-Casault 1.jpg|A branch of the National Archives is found in Pavillon Casault\nLaval University PEPS 03.jpg|Olympic swimming pool inside the PEPS complex\nTelus Stadium, Laval University.jpg|[[TELUS]] stadium\n</gallery>\n\n===Off campus===\nApart from the school of architecture, located in [[Old Quebec]] since 1988,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.arc.ulaval.ca/a-propos/historique.html |title=Historique - \u00c9cole d'architecture |website=Universit\u00e9 Laval |language=fr-FR |access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref> the only out of campus facilities are the school of visual arts in the downtown neighborhood of [[Saint-Roch (Quebec City)|Saint-Roch's]], and the experimental [[Montmorency forest]] ([[:fr:For\u00eat Montmorency|fr]]) ({{cvt|70|km}} north of Quebec City). \n<gallery class=\"center\">\nForet Montmorency - 055.jpg|A facility of the experimental forest\n\u00c9cole architecture ULaval.JPG|The school of architecture\nLa Fabrique - 01.jpg|''La Fabrique'' building hosts the school of art\n</gallery>\n\n==Programs==\nAs of 2002, Universit\u00e9 Laval offered over 350 programs to more than 38,000 students. The university also attracts more than 2,500 foreign students annually, and has almost 1,000 students drawn from Canadian provinces outside of Quebec. Many students come to the university for the ''Fran\u00e7ais pour non-francophones'' program that offers instruction in French as a second language to students from Canada and around the world. It is also the only university in Quebec which trains forestry engineers.{{citation needed|date=July 2016}} Since the mid-1980s, Universit\u00e9 Laval has offered distance learning; over 30 programs and 400 courses are offered by distance learning, of which 80% are accessible from the internet.\n\n==Faculties and schools==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=35em|\n* Administrative Sciences\n* [[Agriculture]] and [[Food science]]s<small>*</small>\n* [[Architecture]], [[Urban planning]] and [[Visual arts]]\n* [[Dentistry]]\n* Education\n* [[Facult\u00e9 de droit (Universit\u00e9 Laval)|Facult\u00e9 de Droit]] (Faculty of Law)\n* Facult\u00e9 des Lettres (Humanities)\n* [[Forestry]], [[Geography]] and [[Geomatics]]<small>**</small>\n* Hautes \u00c9tudes Internationales (HEI)\n* Arts\n* [[Universit\u00e9 Laval Facult\u00e9 de m\u00e9decine|Medicine]]\n* [[Music]]\n* [[Nursing]]\n* [[Pharmacy]]\n* [[Philosophy]]\n* Postgraduate Studies\n* Science and Engineering\n* Social Sciences\n* Theology and Religious Studies\n<small>*</small><small> The D\u00e9partement des Sciences des Aliments et de Nutrition has an accredited dietetic program. The university is accredited by a professional organization such as the [[Dietitians of Canada]] and the university's graduates may subsequently become registered dietitians.</small><br />\n<small>**</small><small> The Faculty is part of the [[Association of University Forestry Schools of Canada|AUFSC]] and has accredited baccalaureate of science programs with specializations in forestry & environmental management; forestry operations (co-op) and forestry engineering.</small>\n}}\n\n{{Canadian university rankings\n| UniName = Universit\u00e9 Laval\n| ARWU_W = 201\u2013300\n| ARWU_CAN = 10\u201312\n| THES_W = 251\u2013300\n| THES_N = 11\u201314\n| QS_W = 416\n| QS_N = 15\n| USNWR_GU = 315\n| USNWR_N = 13\n| MAC_med = 12\n| MAC_rep = 15\n|}}\n\n==Research==\nQu\u00e9bec university holds four of the 19 Canada Excellence Research Chairs awarded nationwide: Canada Excellence Research Chair in Remote Sensing of Canada's New Arctic Frontier, Canada Research Excellence Chair in the Microbiome-Endocannabinoidome Axis in Metabolic Health, Canada Excellence Research Chair in Photonic Innovations, and Communication and Canada Excellence Research Chair in Neurophotonics.<ref>{{cite web|title=Canada Excellence Research Chairs|url=http://www.cerc.gc.ca/chairholders-titulaires/index-eng.aspx|website=www.cerc.gc.ca|accessdate=March 29, 2017|language=en|date=2012-11-29}}</ref> The university has also received research funding from [[Huawei]] but has kept the details of the funding confidential.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/huawei-academic-funding-in-canada-1.5372310|title=Huawei funds $56M in academic research in Canada. That has some experts concerned|last=Armstrong|first=Peter|date=November 29, 2019|work=[[CBC News]]|access-date=December 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nationalpost.com/news/canadian-governments-give-huawei-millions-in-funding-while-debate-rages-over-its-5g-role|title=Canadian governments give Huawei millions in funding while debate rages over its 5G role|last=Blackwell|first=Tom|date=February 3, 2020|work=[[National Post]]|access-date=February 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==University press==\n''Les Presses de l'Universit\u00e9 Laval'', which was founded in 1950, deals with Canadian civilization, literature, medieval studies, law, social sciences, physical sciences and engineering.<ref>[http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/index.cfm?PgNm=TCE&Params=A1ARTA0008267 University Presses<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608081406/http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/index.cfm?PgNm=TCE&Params=A1ARTA0008267 |date=2011-06-08 }}</ref>  It publishes some 120 book per year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pulaval.com/a-propos |title=Presses de l'Universit\u00e9 Laval - Editeur de livres universitaires |publisher=Pulaval.com |date= |accessdate=2018-07-16}}</ref>\n\n==University cooperative==\n{{Main|Zone Coop\u00e9rative de l'Universit\u00e9 Laval}}\nThe ''Coop\u00e9rative de l'Universit\u00e9 Laval'' is engaged in the sale of products to customers throughout the university, such as books, lecture notes and computers.\n\n==Athletics and sports teams==\n{{Main|Laval Rouge et Or}}\n[[File:RTEmagicC logo-Rouge-et-Or png.png|185px|thumb|right|Universit\u00e9 Laval Rouge et Or Logo]] Athletics take place at the [[PEPS|PEPS complex]]. Laval's varsity sports teams are named the [[Laval Rouge-et-Or|Rouge-et-Or]] (Red & Gold). As of 2017, the men's [[Laval Rouge et Or football|football team of Laval]] have won nine [[Vanier Cup]]s since 2003 and has thus the most titles in the country, followed by the [[Western Mustangs football|Western Mustangs]] (6 Vanier Cups).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.tsn.ca/western-s-marshall-hoping-to-end-vanier-cup-drought-on-saturday-against-laval-1.925111 |title=Western's Marshall hoping to win first Vanier Cup  |date=2017-11-24 |website=TSN |access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n{{Main| List of Universit\u00e9 Laval people }}\nPublic figures, including Prime Ministers of Canada, Premiers of Quebec, Supreme Court Justices, federal Cabinet Ministers, Senators, and Lieutenant-Governors as well as national and international athletes have graduated from l'Universit\u00e9 Laval. Some of the more prominent are:\n* [[List of prime ministers of Canada|Prime Ministers of Canada]]: [[Louis St. Laurent]], [[Brian Mulroney]] and [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]]\n* [[List of premiers of Quebec|Premiers of Quebec]]: [[Lucien Bouchard]], [[Pierre-Joseph-Olivier Chauveau]], [[Edmund James Flynn]], [[Jean Lesage]], [[Ren\u00e9 L\u00e9vesque]], [[Pauline Marois]], [[Simon-Napol\u00e9on Parent]] and [[Louis-Alexandre Taschereau]]\n* [[List of Justices of the Supreme Court of Canada|Supreme Court Justices]]: [[Suzanne C\u00f4t\u00e9]], [[Louis LeBel]], [[Claire L'Heureux-Dub\u00e9]], [[Charles Fitzpatrick]], [[Arthur Cyrille Albert Malouin]], [[Lawrence Arthur Dumoulin Cannon]], [[Louis-Philippe Pigeon]], [[Julien Chouinard]], [[Robert Taschereau]], [[Henri-Elz\u00e9ar Taschereau]], [[Thibaudeau Rinfret]]\n\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nGrand Duke Jean 29.09.2006.jpg|[[Jean, Grand Duke of Luxembourg|Jean]], [[Monarchy of Luxembourg|Grand Duke of Luxembourg]].\nLouisstlaurent.jpg|[[Louis St. Laurent]], [[List of Canadian Prime Ministers|12th]] [[Prime Minister of Canada]]. \nMulroney.jpg|[[Brian Mulroney]], 18th Prime Minister of Canada.\nJean Chr\u00e9tien 2010.jpg|[[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]], 20th Prime Mininister of Canada.\nJacques-\u00c9douard Alexis.jpg|[[Jacques-\u00c9douard Alexis]], [[List of Prime Ministers of Haiti|9th]] [[Prime Minister of Haiti]].\nNiklaus Wirth, UrGU.jpg|[[Niklaus Wirth]], designer of several programming languages.\nCharles Fitzpatrick.jpg|[[Charles Fitzpatrick]], 5th [[Chief Justice of Canada]]. \n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of universities in Quebec]]\n* [[List of universities in Canada]]\n* [[Group of Thirteen (Canadian universities)]]\n* [[Laval Thomism]]\n* [[List of oldest universities in continuous operation#Oldest Universities by Region (post 1500)|List of oldest universities by region]]\n* [[Quebec City]]\n* [[Canadian university scientific research organizations]]\n* [[Higher education in Quebec]]\n* [[CHYZ|CHYZ campus radio station]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Universit\u00e9 Laval}}\n* [https://www.ulaval.ca/ Official website]\n* [http://www.bibl.ulaval.ca/ Biblioth\u00e8que de l'Universit\u00e9 Laval]\n* [https://www2.ulaval.ca/en/about-the-foundation.html/ Universit\u00e9 Laval Foundation]\n* [https://www2.ulaval.ca/en/academics/faculties-departments-and-schools/forestry-geography-and-geomatics.html/ Faculty of Forestry, Georgraphy and Geomatics]\n* {{CathEncy|wstitle=Laval University of Quebec|short=x}}\n* {{Cite NSRW|wstitle=Laval University|short=x}}\n\n{{Universit\u00e9 Laval}}\n{{Quebec City}}\n{{U15}}\n{{Qc_Uni}}\n{{ShadUni}}\n{{Universities in Canada}}\n{{Canadian law schools}}\n{{Coord|46|46|48|N|71|16|29|W|type:edu|display=title}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Laval, Universite}}\n[[Category:1663 establishments in the French colonial empire]]\n[[Category:1852 establishments in Canada]]\n[[Category:Education in Quebec City]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in the 1660s]]\n[[Category:Forestry education]]\n[[Category:Universit\u00e9 Laval| ]]\n[[Category:Universities in Quebec]]\n[[Category:Higher education in Canada]]\n[[Category:U15 Group of Canadian Research Universities|Laval]]\n", "name_user": "Freddiem", "label": "safe", "comment": "appropriate link, uniformity in article", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Universit%C3%A9_Laval"}
{"title_page": "Oncosperma tigillarium", "text_new": "{{short description|Species of palm tree}}\n{{Speciesbox\n|image = Oncosperma tigillarium.jpg\n|image_caption = ''Oncosperma tigillarium'' in Malaysia\n|genus = Oncosperma\n|species = tigillarium\n|authority = [[William Jack (botanist)|(Jack)]] [[Henry Nicholas Ridley|Ridl.]]<ref>{{cite journal |last=Vibe Norup |first=M |author2=J Dransfield |author3=MW Chase |author4=AS Barfod |author5=WJ Baker |title=Homoplasious character combinations and generic delimitations: a case study from the Indo-Pacific arecoid palms (Arecaceae: Areceae) |journal=[[American Journal of Botany]] |year=2006 |volume=93 |issue=7 |pages=1065\u20131080 |doi=10.3732/ajb.93.7.1065 |pmid=21642171|url=https://pure.au.dk/ws/files/43885606/Norup_et_al._2006.pdf }}</ref>\n|synonyms = *''Areca tigillaria'' <small>Jack</small>\n*''Keppleria tigillaria'' <small>(Jack) [[Carl Meissner|Meisn.]]</small>\n*''Areca nibung'' <small>Mart.</small>\n*''Areca spinosa'' <small>Hasselt & Kunth</small>\n*''Euterpe filamentosa'' <small>Kunth</small>\n*''Oncosperma filamentosum'' <small>(Kunth) Blume</small>\n*''Oncosperma cambodianum'' <small>Hance</small>\n|synonyms_ref = <ref name=wcsp/>\n}}\n\n'''''Oncosperma tigilarium''''' is a species of [[palm tree]] in the family [[Arecaceae]].\n\n== Description ==\n''Oncosperma tigilarium'' grows to 12m (possibly up to 30m) in height in dense thickets of up to 50 palm trees. The trunks of the palms are covered with long black spines. ''Oncosperma  tigilarium'' has finely pinnate leaves, with drooping leaflets.<ref>[http://www.pacsoa.org.au/palms/Oncosperma/tigillarium.html Palm & Cycad Societies of Australia, ''Oncosperma tigillarium'']</ref><ref>Henderson, A. (2009). Palms of Southern Asia: 1-197. Princeton university press, Princeton and Oxford.</ref><ref>Barfod, A.S. & Dransfield, J. (2013). Flora of Thailand 11(3): 323-498. The Forest Herbarium, National Park, Wildlife and Plant Conservation Department, Bangkok.</ref><ref name=DyPhon>{{cite book |last=Dy Phon |first=Pauline |title=Plants Used In Cambodia/Plantes utilis\u00e9es au Cambodge, Imprimerie Olympic, Phnom Penh |date=2000|page=479|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=InD2RAAACAAJ}}</ref>\n\n==Common names==\nIts common name in [[Indonesian Language|Indonesian]] is ''nibung'' meaning ''thorn'', for the long thorns that arise along the length of the trunk of the palm. In parts of the [[Philippines]] it is known as ''anibung'' in the [[Hiligaynon language]]. In [[Khmer language|Khmer]] it is called sla: ta 'a\u00f4n<ref name=DyPhon />\n\n==Distribution==\nThe species is known from inland, lower salinity waters, near [[mangrove]] swamps of southern [[Vietnam]], [[Cambodia]], the [[Philippines]], [[Malaysia]] and [[Indonesia]], in [[Southeast Asia]].<ref name=wcsp>[http://apps.kew.org/wcsp/namedetail.do?name_id=140160 Kew World Checklist of Selected Plant Families]</ref> It is native to these areas west of the [[Wallace Line]] growing at elevations below 150 metres. It is endangered in some areas due to deforestation, and it is invasive to a few tropical islands in the [[Western Hemisphere]] where it has been planted as an ornamental.\n\n==Habitat and ecology==\nIn [[Singapore]], A cluster of Nibong palms survive near the entrance of the [[Istana]], located at the end of [[Orchard Road]]. A plaque at that site states: \"As the nibong is a mangrove palm, this site must have once been a mangrove swamp.\"<ref>[http://www.nparks.gov.sg/nparks_cms/cms/cmsmgr/data/6/PlantChkList.xls National Parks Board Singapore (2006). Vascular Plant Life Checklist Pulau Ubin. ]</ref> The species is a close relative of ''[[Oncosperma horridum]]'' and shares with it properties of seawater-resistance in its stems, making it useful in the construction of [[kelong|kelongs]], wooden structures used in shallow seas for the catching or cultivation of fish.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\n==Uses==\nIn Cambodia, the black, very hard wood is used for pickets in dams, the manufacture of boards and as ribs in umbrellas. The green fruit may replace [[Areca nut]] in the [[Betel|betel]] quid.<ref name=DyPhon />\n\nThe leaf buds are edible.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hargreaves|first1=Dorothy|last2=Hargreaves|first2=Bob|title=Tropical Trees of the Pacific|year=1970|publisher=Hargreaves|location=Kailua, Hawaii|p=43}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q7092129}}\n\n[[Category:Oncosperma|tigillarium]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1820]]\n[[Category:Trees of Indo-China]]\n[[Category:Trees of Malesia]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Species of palm tree}}\n{{Speciesbox\n|image = Oncosperma tigillarium.jpg\n|image_caption = ''Oncosperma tigillarium'' in Malaysia\n|genus = Oncosperma\n|species = tigillarium\n|authority = [[William Jack (botanist)|(Jack)]] [[Henry Nicholas Ridley|Ridl.]]<ref>{{cite journal |last=Vibe Norup |first=M |author2=J Dransfield |author3=MW Chase |author4=AS Barfod |author5=WJ Baker |title=Homoplasious character combinations and generic delimitations: a case study from the Indo-Pacific arecoid palms (Arecaceae: Areceae) |journal=[[American Journal of Botany]] |year=2006 |volume=93 |issue=7 |pages=1065\u20131080 |doi=10.3732/ajb.93.7.1065 |pmid=21642171|url=https://pure.au.dk/ws/files/43885606/Norup_et_al._2006.pdf }}</ref>\n|synonyms = *''Areca tigillaria'' <small>Jack</small>\n*''Keppleria tigillaria'' <small>(Jack) [[Carl Meissner|Meisn.]]</small>\n*''Areca nibung'' <small>Mart.</small>\n*''Areca spinosa'' <small>Hasselt & Kunth</small>\n*''Euterpe filamentosa'' <small>Kunth</small>\n*''Oncosperma filamentosum'' <small>(Kunth) Blume</small>\n*''Oncosperma cambodianum'' <small>Hance</small>\n|synonyms_ref = <ref name=wcsp/>\n}}\n\n'''''Oncosperma tigilarium''''' is a species of [[palm tree]] in the family [[Arecaceae]].\n\n== Description ==\n''Oncosperma tigilarium'' grows to 12m (possibly up to 30m) in height in dense thickets of up to 50 palm trees. The trunks of the palms are covered with long black spines. ''Oncosperma  tigilarium'' has finely pinnate leaves, with drooping leaflets.<ref>[http://www.pacsoa.org.au/palms/Oncosperma/tigillarium.html Palm & Cycad Societies of Australia, ''Oncosperma tigillarium'']</ref><ref>Henderson, A. (2009). Palms of Southern Asia: 1-197. Princeton university press, Princeton and Oxford.</ref><ref>Barfod, A.S. & Dransfield, J. (2013). Flora of Thailand 11(3): 323-498. The Forest Herbarium, National Park, Wildlife and Plant Conservation Department, Bangkok.</ref><ref name=DyPhon>{{cite book |last=Dy Phon |first=Pauline |title=Plants Used In Cambodia/Plantes utilis\u00e9es au Cambodge, Imprimerie Olympic, Phnom Penh |date=2000}}</ref>\n\n==Common names==\nIts common name in [[Indonesian Language|Indonesian]] is ''nibung'' meaning ''thorn'', for the long thorns that arise along the length of the trunk of the palm. In parts of the [[Philippines]] it is known as ''anibung'' in the [[Hiligaynon language]]. In [[Khmer language|Khmer]] it is called sla: ta 'a\u00f4n<ref name=DyPhon />\n\n==Distribution==\nThe species is known from inland, lower salinity waters, near [[mangrove]] swamps of southern [[Vietnam]], [[Cambodia]], the [[Philippines]], [[Malaysia]] and [[Indonesia]], in [[Southeast Asia]].<ref name=wcsp>[http://apps.kew.org/wcsp/namedetail.do?name_id=140160 Kew World Checklist of Selected Plant Families]</ref> It is native to these areas west of the [[Wallace Line]] growing at elevations below 150 metres. It is endangered in some areas due to deforestation, and it is invasive to a few tropical islands in the [[Western Hemisphere]] where it has been planted as an ornamental.\n\n==Habitat and ecology==\nIn [[Singapore]], A cluster of Nibong palms survive near the entrance of the [[Istana]], located at the end of [[Orchard Road]]. A plaque at that site states: \"As the nibong is a mangrove palm, this site must have once been a mangrove swamp.\"<ref>[http://www.nparks.gov.sg/nparks_cms/cms/cmsmgr/data/6/PlantChkList.xls National Parks Board Singapore (2006). Vascular Plant Life Checklist Pulau Ubin. ]</ref> The species is a close relative of ''[[Oncosperma horridum]]'' and shares with it properties of seawater-resistance in its stems, making it useful in the construction of [[kelong|kelongs]], wooden structures used in shallow seas for the catching or cultivation of fish.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\n==Uses==\nIn Cambodia, the black, very hard wood is used for pickets in dams, the manufacture of boards and as ribs in umbrellas. The green fruit may replace [[Areca nut]] in the [[Betel|betel]] quid.<ref name=DyPhon />\n\nThe leaf buds are edible.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hargreaves|first1=Dorothy|last2=Hargreaves|first2=Bob|title=Tropical Trees of the Pacific|year=1970|publisher=Hargreaves|location=Kailua, Hawaii|p=43}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q7092129}}\n\n[[Category:Oncosperma|tigillarium]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1820]]\n[[Category:Trees of Indo-China]]\n[[Category:Trees of Malesia]]\n", "name_user": "Brunswicknic", "label": "safe", "comment": "url", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oncosperma_tigillarium"}
{"title_page": "Elton Ahi", "text_new": "{{short description|Persian music producer from in Iran|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|name = Elton Ahi\n|image = ahi5 hi.jpg\n|image_size  = 250\n|alt     = \n|caption = Elton Ahi\n|birth_name = Farokh Ahi<br>{{lang-fa|\u0641\u0631\u062e \u0622\u0647\u06cc}}\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1964|08|06}}\n|origin = [[Iran]]\n|background = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n|occupation = [[Music Producer]], [[DJ]], [[Songwriter]]\n|years_active =  1972\u2013present\n|Instruments = [[Drums]], [[Guitar]], [[Piano]]\n}}\n\n'''Elton Ahi''' ({{lang-fa|\u0627\u0644\u062a\u0648\u0646 \u0622\u0647\u06cc}}, also credited as '''Elton Farokh Ahi''', Persian: {{lang|fa|\u0627\u0644\u062a\u0648\u0646 \u0641\u0631\u062e \u0622\u0647\u06cc}}; born 1964) is a Persian music producer from [[Iran]].<ref name=\"iranian.com\">{{cite web | title = Hit Machine: Interview with Legendary Music Producer Elton Farokh Ahi | url = http://www.iranian.com/Music/2007/July/Ahi/index.html}}</ref> He has been credited with music production/ editing/ sound engineering for over 100 Hollywood major motion pictures including: [[xXx (film)|xXx]], [[The Mummy: Tomb of the Dragon Emperor]], [[27 Dresses]], and [[The Last of the Mohicans]], which won an Oscar for sound.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mummy: Tomb of the Dragon Emperor Mixed on Equator Audio Research Q10 Studio Monitors |url=http://www.equatoraudio.com/mummy.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091202093828/http://www.equatoraudio.com/mummy.htm |archivedate=2 December 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\nElton Ahi began his musical career at the age of 15, writing and producing the Iranian album, \u201cDestination.\u201d<ref>{{cite web | title = Destination From Beginning to End CD | url = http://www.cduniverse.com/search/xx/music/pid/1068267/a/From+Beginning+To+End.htm}}</ref> He started college at USC at a very young age, studying architecture while pursuing his side interest of music by drumming in an American band. After completing his degree, he began DJing and giving consulting services to record labels. He won US \u201cDJ of the Year\u201d in 1977, spinning for such famous clubs as [[Studio 54]] in [[New York City]] and Jimmy\u2019s in [[Monaco]].  Ahi has produced [[Hamsayehaa]], the best-selling Persian album of all time. He has also been credited with being influential in the careers of Persian artists, Andy & Kouros, Siavash and Farez.<ref>{{cite web | title = Voice of Farsi Programme: Exclusive Interview with Farez | url = http://voiceoffarsi.blogspot.com/search?q=Elton+Ahi&updated-max=2009-10-10T05%3A58%3A00-07%3A00&max-results=20}}</ref> Elton Ahi currently owns Rusk studios in [[Los Angeles]], recording house for artists such as [[Donna Summer]], [[Billy Idol]], [[Laura Branigan]], and [[Elton John]].<ref>{{cite news |last=IndiaPost Voice of Indian's Worldwide |title=Bappi Discovery in Hollywood |url=http://www.indiapost.com/life-style/8109-Racquelle-Heffernan.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100823215936/http://www.indiapost.com/life-style/8109-Racquelle-Heffernan.html |archivedate=23 August 2010 |df=dmy }}</ref> He co-produced [[Engelbert Humperdinck (singer)|Engelbert Humperdinck]] and the [[Patsy Cline]] \"Duets\" album with record producer [[Michael Blakey (Media Executive)]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Patsy Cline Duests, Volume 1 | url = http://www.patsified.com/records/4634170972.html}}</ref> Elton Ahi has also written songs for artists such as [[Mansour (singer)|Mansour]], a contemporary Persian artist. Ahi adopted  the moniker \u201cElton\u201d when a radio station interview in [[Iran]] dubbed him \u201cElton Joon\u201d after recording some [[Elton John]] songs.<ref name=\"iranian.com\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|0013941}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ahi, Elton}}\n[[Category:American record producers]]\n[[Category:Iranian record producers]]\n[[Category:American people of Iranian descent]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n[[Category:Iranian music arrangers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Persian music producer from in Iran|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|name = Elton Ahi\n|image = ahi5 hi.jpg\n|image_size  = 250\n|alt     = \n|caption = Elton Ahi\n|birth_name = Farokh Ahi<br>{{lang-fa|\u0641\u0631\u062e \u0622\u0647\u06cc}}\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1964|08|06}}\n|origin = [[Iran]]\n|background = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n|occupation = [[Music Producer]], [[DJ]], [[Songwriter]]\n|years_active =  1972\u2013present\n|Instruments = [[Drums]], [[Guitar]], [[Piano]]\n}}\n\n'''Elton Ahi''' ({{lang-fa|\u0627\u0644\u062a\u0648\u0646 \u0622\u0647\u06cc}}, also credited as '''Elton Farokh Ahi''', Persian: {{lang|fa|\u0627\u0644\u062a\u0648\u0646 \u0641\u0631\u062e \u0622\u0647\u06cc}}; born 1964) is a Persian music producer from [[Iran]].<ref name=\"iranian.com\">{{cite web | title = Hit Machine: Interview with Legendary Music Producer Elton Farokh Ahi | url = http://www.iranian.com/Music/2007/July/Ahi/index.html}}</ref> He has been credited with music production/ editing/ sound engineering for over 100 Hollywood major motion pictures including: [[xXx (film)|xXx]], [[The Mummy: Tomb of the Dragon Emperor]], [[27 Dresses]], and [[The Last of the Mohicans]], which won an Oscar for sound.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mummy: Tomb of the Dragon Emperor Mixed on Equator Audio Research Q10 Studio Monitors |url=http://www.equatoraudio.com/mummy.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091202093828/http://www.equatoraudio.com/mummy.htm |archivedate=2 December 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\nElton Ahi began his musical career at the age of 15, writing and producing the Iranian album, \u201cDestination.\u201d<ref>{{cite web | title = Destination From Beginning to End CD | url = http://www.cduniverse.com/search/xx/music/pid/1068267/a/From+Beginning+To+End.htm}}</ref> He started college at USC at a very young age, studying architecture while pursuing his side interest of music by drumming in an American band. After completing his degree, he began DJ-ing and giving consulting services to record labels. He won US \u201cDJ of the Year\u201d in 1977, spinning for such famous clubs as [[Studio 54]] in [[New York City]] and Jimmy\u2019s in [[Monaco]].  Ahi has produced [[Hamsayehaa]], the best-selling Persian album of all time. He has also been credited with being influential in the careers of Persian artists, Andy & Kouros, Siavash and Farez.<ref>{{cite web | title = Voice of Farsi Programme: Exclusive Interview with Farez | url = http://voiceoffarsi.blogspot.com/search?q=Elton+Ahi&updated-max=2009-10-10T05%3A58%3A00-07%3A00&max-results=20}}</ref> Elton Ahi currently owns Rusk studios in [[Los Angeles]], recording house for artists such as [[Donna Summer]], [[Billy Idol]], [[Laura Branigan]], and [[Elton John]].<ref>{{cite news |last=IndiaPost Voice of Indian's Worldwide |title=Bappi Discovery in Hollywood |url=http://www.indiapost.com/life-style/8109-Racquelle-Heffernan.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100823215936/http://www.indiapost.com/life-style/8109-Racquelle-Heffernan.html |archivedate=23 August 2010 |df=dmy }}</ref> He co-produced [[Engelbert Humperdinck (singer)|Engelbert Humperdinck]] and the [[Patsy Cline]] \"Duets\" album with record producer [[Michael Blakey (Media Executive)]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Patsy Cline Duests, Volume 1 | url = http://www.patsified.com/records/4634170972.html}}</ref> Elton Ahi has also written songs for artists such as [[Mansour (singer)|Mansour]], a contemporary Persian artist. Ahi adopted  the moniker \u201cElton\u201d when a radio station interview in [[Iran]] dubbed him \u201cElton Joon\u201d after recording some [[Elton John]] songs.<ref name=\"iranian.com\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|0013941}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ahi, Elton}}\n[[Category:American record producers]]\n[[Category:Iranian record producers]]\n[[Category:American people of Iranian descent]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n[[Category:Iranian music arrangers]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elton_Ahi"}
{"title_page": "Caprigliola bridge collapse", "text_new": "{{Short description|260 m road bridge collapsed in Italy on 08 April 2020}}\n{{Current disaster|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox bridge\n| name                = \n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| image               = \n| image_upright       = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| pushpin_map         = \n| pushpin_relief      = \n| pushpin_map_size    = \n| pushpin_map_alt     = \n| pushpin_map_caption = \n| coordinates         = {{coord|44|10|26.4|N|09|55|31.7|E|display=inline}}\n| os_grid_reference   = \n| qid                 = \n| refs                = \n| carries             = \n| crosses             = \n| locale              = \n| starts              = \n| ends                = \n| official_name       = \n| other_name          = \n| named_for           = \n| owner               = [[ANAS]]\n| maint               = \n| heritage            = \n| id                  = \n| id_type             = \n| website             = \n| preceded            = \n| followed            = \n| design              = \n| material            = [[Reinforced concrete]]\n| material1           = \n| material2           = \n| length              = {{convert|260|m|abbr=on}}\n| width               = {{convert|7.2|m|abbr=on}}\n| height              = {{convert|10|m|abbr=on}}\n| depth               = \n| traversable         = \n| towpath             = \n| mainspan            = \n| number_spans        = \n| piers_in_water      = \n| load                = \n| clearance_above     = \n| clearance_below     = \n| lanes               = \n| life                = \n| first_length        = \n| first_diameter      = \n| second_length       = \n| second_diameter     = \n| third_length        = \n| third_diameter      = \n| capacity            = \n| num_track           = \n| track_gauge         = \n| structure_gauge     = \n| electrification     = \n| architect           = Attilio Muggia<ref name=\"News1\" />\n| designer            = \n| contracted_designer = \n| winner              = \n| engineering         = \n| builder             = Ing. Nino Ferrari Impresa Costruzioni Generali Srl\n| fabricator          = \n| begin               = 1906\n| complete            = 1908\n| cost                = \n| open                = October 1908\n| inaugurated         = 11 October 1908\n| rebuilt             = 1945\u20131949 after being mined by the German [[Wermacht]] in 1945\n| collapsed           = 8 April 2020\n| closed              = \n| replaces            = \n| replaced_by         = \n| traffic             = \n| toll                = \n| map_type            = \n| map_relief          = \n| map_dot_label       = \n| map_image           = Caprigliola bridge collapse Location.png\n| map_size            = \n| map_alt             = \n| mapframe            = \n| mapframe_zoom       = \n| mapframe_width      = \n| mapframe_height     = \n| mapframe_marker     = \n| mapframe_marker_color = \n| mapframe_lat        = \n| mapframe_long       = \n| map_caption         = Location of the collapsed Caprigliola bridge on the [[Magra]] river between [[Caprigliola]] and [[Albiano Magra]] in [[Tuscany]]\n| extra               = <!-- extra = module = embed = -->\n}}\n\nOn 8 April 2020 at 10:25&nbsp;am local time (8:25 UTC), a {{convert|260|m|adj=on}} long road bridge on the SS330 road near the town of [[Aulla]] between the villages of [[Caprigliola]] and [[Albiano Magra]] at mid-way between [[Genoa]] and [[Florence]] collapsed into the [[Magra]] river. The traffic on the bridge was unusually light due to the [[2020 Italy coronavirus lockdown|coronavirus lockdown]] then in force, and the collapse resulted in only minor injuries of two truck drivers.<ref name=\"BBC_News_April_08\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-52213898 |title=Italy bridge collapse: Two drivers survive |work=BBC News |date=8 April 2020 |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Lockdown keeps casualty figure low as Italian bridge collapses |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/08/lockdown-keeps-casualty-figure-low-as-italian-bridge-collapses |date=8 April 2020 |accessdate=9 April 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Bridge Collapses in Italy, Newest Crumbling Infrastructure |url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/04/08/world/europe/bc-eu-italy-bridge-collapse.html |accessdate=9 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.voceapuana.com/fotogallery/crollato-il-ponte-sul-magra-disastro-ad-776_1.aspx|title=Crollato il ponte sul Magra, disastro ad Albiano|work=La Voce Apuana|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Euronews]], a gas pipeline was damaged but the gas leak was promptly isolated by [[Italgas]].<ref name=\"Euronews_1\">[https://www.euronews.com/2020/04/08/italian-bridge-collapses-injuring-only-one-as-lockdown-conditions-reduce-traffic Euronews: Italian bridge collapses injuring only one as lockdown conditions reduce traffic] </ref>\n\n==History==\n\nThe bridge was located on the river Marra at about {{convert|9|km}} south from the town of Aulla, a [[comune]] in the [[province of Massa and Carrara]], [[Tuscany]] in central Italy.\nIn November 2019, a crack on the road pavement was reported by bridge users after heavy rainfall.<ref name=\"BBC_News_April_08\" /> [[ANAS|ANAS S.p.A.]] (''Azienda Nazionale Autonoma delle Strade'', English: ''National Autonomous Roads Corporation''), was in charge of the maintenance of the bridge. After reports by drivers, ANAS carried out an inspection of the bridge, finding no anomalies or defects requiring emergency repairs. A crack in the road pavement was then repaired with fresh asphalt. {{As of|2020|04|09}}, the root cause of the bridge collapse is unknown but a small event may have triggered a more significant one, compromising the structural stability of the bridge. \n\n===Construction===\n\n[[Attilio Muggia]], a pioneer of [[reinforced concrete]] in Italy, built the bridge on the Magra river for connecting Albiano with Caprigliola and [[Tuscany]] with [[Liguria]].<ref name =\"News1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.news1.news/a/2020/04/collapsed-bridge-it-was-from-1908-it-was-built-by-a-pioneer-of-reinforced-concrete.html|title=Collapsed bridge: it was from 1908, it was built by a pioneer of reinforced concrete|date=9 April 2020|publisher=|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Levantenews\">{{cite web|url=http://www.levantenews.it/index.php/2020/04/09/aulla-un-crollo-deja-vu/|title=Aulla: a collapse d\u00e9j\u00e0 vu|publisher=|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref name =\"Voceapuana_1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.voceapuana.com/lunigiana-e-apuane/attualita/-il-ponte-costruito-da-mio-nonno-era-sopravvissuto-alle-mine-tedesche-27210.aspx|title=\"Il ponte costruito da mio nonno, era sopravvissuto alle mine tedesche\"|date=8 April 2020|work=La Voce Apuana|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe bridge construction began in 1906 and was achieved in October 1908. The five slender arches had a span of {{convert|51.15|m}} and the deck was supported by 400 pillars. The construction works required {{convert|3000|t|ST|abbr=on}} of cement and {{convert|220|t|ST|abbr=on}} of iron. After the bridge commissioning, the ferry service on the Magra river was abandoned.<ref name=\"News1\" /><ref name=\"Voceapuana_1\" />\n\n===Damage in World War II===\n\nThe bridge was badly damaged at the end of World War II by mines set by the German [[Wehrmacht]] in 1945. It was repaired between 1945 and 1949, when the upper parts of the bridge and its deck were reconstructed, retaining the original lower parts of the bridge.<ref name=\"Voceapuana_1\" />\n\n==Controversy about safety==\n\nThe Municipality of Aulla and local inhabitants had previously questioned the safety of the bridge. In a August 2019 letter, Vincenzo Marzi, then head of the ANAS department for Tuscany, replied that \"The viaduct for the moment does not present criticalities such as to compromise its static functionality\". This was before the discovery of a crack in the asphalt of the road in November 2019.<ref name=\"Euronews_2\">[https://www.news1.news/a/2020/04/ponte-collapsed-who-is-the-anas-manager-who-signed-the-letter-of-tutto-a-posto.html Ponte collapsed, who is the Anas manager who signed the letter of \"Tutto a posto\"] </ref>\n\n==Root causes of the disaster==\n\nAlthough the root causes of the collapse of the bridge like a house of cards are not yet identified, some conjectures have already been put forwards by some experts. Indeed, ''Voce Apuana'' reports that the engineer Fabrizio Ferrari, nephew of Nino Ferrari who constructed the bridge together with Professor Muggia between 1906 and 1908, told his speculations to CDS: {{Quote|text=\"His impression is that there has been a break due to a cut of a section of the deck at a support. The piles, however, still seem in place. A capital has rotated, perhaps dragged by the deck that passed over it, but the bulk of the pile, the one in the riverbed is intact. The piles are very deep, I doubt that the explanations for this collapse lie in the fact that you are in the river bed. Whether it is a failure of the deck.\"<ref name=\"Voceapuana_1\" />}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ponte Morandi#Collapse|Ponte Morandi]]\u2014A road viaduct in [[Genoa]] that collapsed in 2018\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.voceapuana.com/fotogallery/crollato-il-ponte-sul-magra-disastro-ad-776_1.aspx La Voce Apuana: Collapse of the Caprigliola bridge]\n* [https://www.controradio.it/albiano-magra-anas-scrisse-fatta-ispezione-niente-anomalie/ Controradio: Albiano Magra, Anas wrote 'inspection done, no anomalies']\n* [https://www.ilfogliettone.it/crolla-ponte-sul-magra-tra-liguria-e-toscana-2-mezzi-coinvolti/ Ilfogliettone.it: Bridge collapses over the Magra river between Liguria and Tuscany, 2 vehicles involved]\n* Video: [https://tg24.sky.it/cronaca/2020/04/08/ponte-crollato-albiano-sindaco-aulla.html Bridge collapse near Aulla]\n\n[[Category:2020 in Italy]]\n[[Category:2020 road incidents]]\n[[Category:21st century in Tuscany]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in Europe]]\n[[Category:Bridge disasters in Italy]]\n[[Category:Bridge disasters of unknown cause]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures demolished in 2020]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Italy]]\n[[Category:Road bridges in Italy]]\n[[Category:Viaducts]]\n\n{{Italy-bridge-struct-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|260 m road bridge collapsed in Italy on 08 April 2020}}\n{{Current disaster|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox bridge\n| name                = \n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| image               = \n| image_upright       = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| pushpin_map         = \n| pushpin_relief      = \n| pushpin_map_size    = \n| pushpin_map_alt     = \n| pushpin_map_caption = \n| coordinates         = {{coord|44|10|26.4|N|09|55|31.7|E|display=inline}}\n| os_grid_reference   = \n| qid                 = \n| refs                = \n| carries             = \n| crosses             = \n| locale              = \n| starts              = \n| ends                = \n| official_name       = \n| other_name          = \n| named_for           = \n| owner               = [[ANAS]]\n| maint               = \n| heritage            = \n| id                  = \n| id_type             = \n| website             = \n| preceded            = \n| followed            = \n| design              = \n| material            = [[Reinforced concrete]]\n| material1           = \n| material2           = \n| length              = {{convert|260|m|abbr=on}}\n| width               = {{convert|7.2|m|abbr=on}}\n| height              = {{convert|10|m|abbr=on}}\n| depth               = \n| traversable         = \n| towpath             = \n| mainspan            = \n| number_spans        = \n| piers_in_water      = \n| load                = \n| clearance_above     = \n| clearance_below     = \n| lanes               = \n| life                = \n| first_length        = \n| first_diameter      = \n| second_length       = \n| second_diameter     = \n| third_length        = \n| third_diameter      = \n| capacity            = \n| num_track           = \n| track_gauge         = \n| structure_gauge     = \n| electrification     = \n| architect           = Attilio Muggia<ref name=\"News1\" />\n| designer            = \n| contracted_designer = \n| winner              = \n| engineering         = \n| builder             = Ing. Nino Ferrari Impresa Costruzioni Generali Srl\n| fabricator          = \n| begin               = 1906\n| complete            = 1908\n| cost                = \n| open                = October 1908\n| inaugurated         = 11 October 1908\n| rebuilt             = 1945\u20131949 after being mined by the German [[Wermacht]] in 1945\n| collapsed           = 8 April 2020\n| closed              = \n| replaces            = \n| replaced_by         = \n| traffic             = \n| toll                = \n| map_type            = \n| map_relief          = \n| map_dot_label       = \n| map_image           = Caprigliola bridge collapse Location.png\n| map_size            = \n| map_alt             = \n| mapframe            = \n| mapframe_zoom       = \n| mapframe_width      = \n| mapframe_height     = \n| mapframe_marker     = \n| mapframe_marker_color = \n| mapframe_lat        = \n| mapframe_long       = \n| map_caption         = Location of the collapsed Caprigliola bridge on the [[Magra]] river between [[Caprigliola]] and [[Albiano Magra]] in [[Tuscany]]\n| extra               = <!-- extra = module = embed = -->\n}}\n\nOn 8 April 2020 at 10:25&nbsp;am local time (8:25 UTC), a {{convert|260|m|adj=on}} long road bridge on the SS330 road near the town of [[Aulla]] between the villages of [[Caprigliola]] and [[Albiano Magra]] at mid-way between [[Genoa]] and [[Florence]] collapsed into the [[Magra]] river. The traffic on the bridge was unusually light due to the [[2020 Italy coronavirus lockdown|coronavirus lockdown]] then in force, and the collapse resulted in only minor injuries of two truck drivers.<ref name=\"BBC_News_April_08\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-52213898 |title=Italy bridge collapse: Two drivers survive |work=BBC News |date=8 April 2020 |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Lockdown keeps casualty figure low as Italian bridge collapses |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/08/lockdown-keeps-casualty-figure-low-as-italian-bridge-collapses |date=8 April 2020 |accessdate=9 April 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Bridge Collapses in Italy, Newest Crumbling Infrastructure |url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/04/08/world/europe/bc-eu-italy-bridge-collapse.html |accessdate=9 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.voceapuana.com/fotogallery/crollato-il-ponte-sul-magra-disastro-ad-776_1.aspx|title=Crollato il ponte sul Magra, disastro ad Albiano|work=La Voce Apuana|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Euronews]], a gas pipeline was damaged but the gas leak was promptly isolated by [[Italgas]].<ref name=\u201dEuronews_1\u201d>[https://www.euronews.com/2020/04/08/italian-bridge-collapses-injuring-only-one-as-lockdown-conditions-reduce-traffic Euronews: Italian bridge collapses injuring only one as lockdown conditions reduce traffic] </ref>\n\n==History==\n\nThe bridge was located on the river Marra at about {{convert|9|km}} south from the town of Aulla, a [[comune]] in the [[province of Massa and Carrara]], [[Tuscany]] in central Italy.\nIn November 2019, a crack on the road pavement was reported by bridge users after heavy rainfall.<ref name=\"BBC_News_April_08\" /> [[ANAS|ANAS S.p.A.]] (''Azienda Nazionale Autonoma delle Strade'', English: ''National Autonomous Roads Corporation''), was in charge of the maintenance of the bridge. After reports by drivers, ANAS carried out an inspection of the bridge, finding no anomalies or defects requiring emergency repairs. A crack in the road pavement was then repaired with fresh asphalt. {{As of|2020|04|09}}, the root cause of the bridge collapse is unknown but a small event may have triggered a more significant one, compromising the structural stability of the bridge. \n\n===Construction===\n\n[[Attilio Muggia]], a pioneer of [[reinforced concrete]] in Italy, built the bridge on the Magra river for connecting Albiano with Caprigliola and [[Tuscany]] with [[Liguria]].<ref name =\"News1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.news1.news/a/2020/04/collapsed-bridge-it-was-from-1908-it-was-built-by-a-pioneer-of-reinforced-concrete.html|title=Collapsed bridge: it was from 1908, it was built by a pioneer of reinforced concrete|date=9 April 2020|publisher=|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Levantenews\">{{cite web|url=http://www.levantenews.it/index.php/2020/04/09/aulla-un-crollo-deja-vu/|title=Aulla: a collapse d\u00e9j\u00e0 vu|publisher=|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref name =\"Voceapuana_1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.voceapuana.com/lunigiana-e-apuane/attualita/-il-ponte-costruito-da-mio-nonno-era-sopravvissuto-alle-mine-tedesche-27210.aspx|title=\"Il ponte costruito da mio nonno, era sopravvissuto alle mine tedesche\"|date=8 April 2020|work=La Voce Apuana|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe bridge construction began in 1906 and was achieved in October 1908. The five slender arches had a span of {{convert|51.15|m}} and the deck was supported by 400 pillars. The construction works required {{convert|3000|t|ST|abbr=on}} of cement and {{convert|220|t|ST|abbr=on}} of iron. After the bridge commissioning, the ferry service on the Magra river was abandoned.<ref name=\"News1\" /><ref name=\"Voceapuana_1\" />\n\n===Damage in World War II===\n\nThe bridge was badly damaged at the end of World War II by mines set by the German [[Wehrmacht]] in 1945. It was repaired between 1945 and 1949, when the upper parts of the bridge and its deck were reconstructed, retaining the original lower parts of the bridge.<ref name=\"Voceapuana_1\" />\n\n==Controversy about safety==\n\nThe Municipality of Aulla and local inhabitants had previously questioned the safety of the bridge. In a August 2019 letter, Vincenzo Marzi, then head of the ANAS department for Tuscany, replied that \"The viaduct for the moment does not present criticalities such as to compromise its static functionality\". This was before the discovery of a crack in the asphalt of the road in November 2019.<ref name=\u201dEuronews_2\u201d>[https://www.news1.news/a/2020/04/ponte-collapsed-who-is-the-anas-manager-who-signed-the-letter-of-tutto-a-posto.html Ponte collapsed, who is the Anas manager who signed the letter of \u201cTutto a posto\u201d] </ref>\n\n==Root causes of the disaster==\n\nAlthough the root causes of the collapse of the bridge like a house of cards are not yet identified, some conjectures have already been put forwards by some experts. Indeed, ''Voce Apuana'' reports that the engineer Fabrizio Ferrari, nephew of Nino Ferrari who constructed the bridge together with Professor Muggia between 1906 and 1908, told his speculations to CDS: {{Quote|text=\"His impression is that there has been a break due to a cut of a section of the deck at a support. The piles, however, still seem in place. A capital has rotated, perhaps dragged by the deck that passed over it, but the bulk of the pile, the one in the riverbed is intact. The piles are very deep, I doubt that the explanations for this collapse lie in the fact that you are in the river bed. Whether it is a failure of the deck.\"<ref name=\"Voceapuana_1\" />}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ponte Morandi#Collapse|Ponte Morandi]]\u2014A road viaduct in [[Genoa]] that collapsed in 2018\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.voceapuana.com/fotogallery/crollato-il-ponte-sul-magra-disastro-ad-776_1.aspx La Voce Apuana: Collapse of the Caprigliola bridge]\n* [https://www.controradio.it/albiano-magra-anas-scrisse-fatta-ispezione-niente-anomalie/ Controradio: Albiano Magra, Anas wrote 'inspection done, no anomalies']\n* [https://www.ilfogliettone.it/crolla-ponte-sul-magra-tra-liguria-e-toscana-2-mezzi-coinvolti/ Ilfogliettone.it: Bridge collapses over the Magra river between Liguria and Tuscany, 2 vehicles involved]\n* Video: [https://tg24.sky.it/cronaca/2020/04/08/ponte-crollato-albiano-sindaco-aulla.html Bridge collapse near Aulla]\n\n[[Category:2020 in Italy]]\n[[Category:2020 road incidents]]\n[[Category:21st century in Tuscany]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in Europe]]\n[[Category:Bridge disasters in Italy]]\n[[Category:Bridge disasters of unknown cause]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures demolished in 2020]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Italy]]\n[[Category:Road bridges in Italy]]\n[[Category:Viaducts]]\n\n{{Italy-bridge-struct-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Verbcatcher", "label": "safe", "comment": "standard quote marks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caprigliola_bridge_collapse"}
